<HEADLINE> Afghan Warring Parties Agree to Ceasefire: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
and opposition representatives have agreed to a ceasefire in their
talks in Turkmenistan, a report reaching here said Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Taliban officials and representatives of opposition commander
Ahmed Shah Masood on Thursday signed a preliminary agreement on
captives exchange and conditions for a ceasefire in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The two sides began the talks under the aegis of the United
Nations on Wednesday in Asghabad, capital of Turkmenistan, a venue
both sides deemed neutral.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a U.N. spokeswoman as saying that the talks
were informal and didn't have a detailed agenda, but were an
attempt to establish a dialogue between the Taliban and the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the two warring parties met at the
negotiating table since last May.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
