<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jets Attack Iraqi Targets in Northern No-Fly Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Following Wednesday's
bombing at Iraqi air defense site, U.S. fighter jets launched new
attacks on Thursday against at least five Iraqi targets in the
northern no-fly zone, including two communications sites and a
surface-to-air missile system.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Steve Campbell said there was no
damage to U.S. aircraft and no injuries to U.S. pilots. Damage
to Iraqi forces was currently being assessed.
</P>
<P>
In the first incident, between about 12:15 p.m. and 12:30
p.m. (0915 and 0930 GMT), a U.S. Air force F-15E strike Eagle
observed Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery fire and was
"illuminated" by an Iraqi radar system near the northern city of
Mosul.
</P>
<P>
"Acting in self-defense, one F-15E dropped four GBU12
precision-guided bombs on a surface-to-air missile
communications site," a Defense Department statement said. Two
other F-15Es launched a missile and dropped four bombs on an
Iraqi surface-to-air missile system.
</P>
<P>
An hour later, U.S. pilots retaliated in three separate
incidents, with F-15Es bombing a SAM site and a communications
site, and an Air force F-16CJ launching a high-speed
anti-radiation missile at an Iraqi radar site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
