<HEADLINE> Civilians Killed in U.S.-British Missile Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi civilians were
killed and several others injured on Thursday when U.S.-British
warplanes attacked civilian targets in northern Iraq, an Iraqi
military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency as saying
that at 11:35 a.m. local time (0835 GMT), 11 formations of
U.S.-British warplanes from a Turkish military base violated
Iraq's northern airspace and fired 16 missiles at the Iraqi air
defense sites in Dohuk and Neineva provinces.
</P>
<P>
U.S.-British warplanes, supported by early warning planes, also
launched missiles at civilian targets in Neineva province, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that Iraqi anti-aircraft units and warplanes
counter-attacked U.S.-British warplanes and hit one of them,
forcing the rest to flee.
</P>
<P>
Around noon, nine formations of U.S.-British warplanes from
Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated Iraq's southern airspace, said
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, one Iraqi civilian was killed and several others
injured when U.S. warplanes attacked the southern Iraqi city of
Najaf.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and its allies imposed no-fly zones in Iraq in the
wake of the 1991 Gulf War, with a claimed aim to protect the Kurds
in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the south from "Baghdad's
suppression."
</P>
<P>
In mid-December the U.S. and Britain air-raided Iraq to
retaliate what they claimed Iraq's non-cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors in charge of eliminating prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
After the air attacks, Iraq announced that it does not
recognize the no-fly zones and would fire at patrolling U.S. and
British jets. Clashes between Iraqi air defense units and
U.S.-British warplanes have almost become daily occurrences.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. and British warplanes bombed three
residential quarters in southern Iraq, killing dozens of civilians
and injuring nearly 100 others.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said earlier Thursday
that Iraq would go on confronting U.S.-British warplanes violating
Iraqi airspace regardless of the sacrifices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
