<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Not to Quicken Pace for Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Referring to the recommendations by a government-invited
international advisory panel to slash the original time-frame for
opening up the banking sector from five years to three years, Lee
said MAS will be sticking to the original time-frame but making
bold moves in the earliest years.
</P>
<P>
He also said MAS is reviewing all restrictions in domestic
banking including limits on opening additional branches, setting
up off-premises ATMs and participating in shared ATM network.
</P>
<P>
MAS will review the rules governing foreign banks granted
offshore licenses to see how reputable bank can have greater
access to the domestic market, Lee added.
</P>
<P>
Lee conceded present regulations for local banks are more
generous in certain instances than for foreign banks
</P>
<P>
But Lee argued that foreign banks already have wide access to
his country's banking sector, saying they enjoy more than a third
of total resident deposits, 45 percent of loans to resident
borrowers and the bulk of the business with non-residents.
</P>
<P>
Lee expressed the hopes that more than one local bank will
develop a significant presence in Asian and international markets
and strengthen their capabilities in corporate banking and
non-traditional, free-based business.
</P>
<P>
He said MAS will give a push to developing fund management. He
said the Government Investment Corporation (GIC) has placed out a
total of 16.9 billion Singapore dollars (about 10 billion U.S.
dollars) to fund management companies with offices in Singapore as
at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The GIC had placed out 6.8 billion Singapore dollars (about 4
billion U.S. dollars) last year after it had announced last
February that it would place out 25 billion Singapore dollars
(about 15 billion U.S. dollars) over the next three years, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
