<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Largest Steelmaker to Come in to Being </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Lower Saxony state
Economics Minister Peter Fischer confirmed Thursday that talks
were underway on a possible merger of the Salzgitter AG steel
company with the Arbed group of Luxembourg, which led to create a
Europe's largest steelmaker.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Salzgitter's two chief shareholders, Lower
Saxony and the North German State Bank (Nord/LB), and Arbed have
been underway since December 23, according to a report of the
German Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
In a merger, Arbed would gain a clear majority of Salzgitter,
the company which was separated from the Preussag concern last
year in a transaction in which Lower Saxony and Nord/LB acquired
controlling interest to avoid a takeover by the Austrian company
Voest.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, of the state's ruling Social Democrats (SPD), drew a
contrast between the two transactions.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the effort to ward off Voest which would have
meant the "selloff" of Salzgitter, the talks with Arbed were aimed
at achieving a partnership, he said.
</P>
<P>
A stock swap would give Lower Saxony and Nord/LB the second
biggest stake in Arbed after the 30 percent share owned by
Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Under the Arbed umbrella, a steel holding to be led by
Salzgitter would be established, to include Arbed's two steel
holdings in Germany, one in Bremen the other in the state of
Thueringen.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Arbed was Europe's second largest steel producer at 19
million tons. Adding Salzgitter's 4.9 million tons capacity would
create Europe's largest steel concern, surpassing
Usinor-Cockerill, at 22.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Lower Saxony and Nord/LB between them own a 67 percent stake in
Salzgitter.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Christian Democratic Union and Greens politicians
demanded an immediate public explanation by Lower Saxony Premier
Gerhard Glogowski about the Arbed talks.
</P>
<P>
Union officials were also alarmed, warning they would try to
block any merger which did not assure the workers' side of
influence in management decisions under current German steel
industry rules.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
