<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Parliament Member Visits Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- European Parliament member
Glenys Kinnoick has started her three-day working visit in
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Kinnoick, who is also vice chairman of the joint assembly of
the European Union - African, Caribbean and Pacific countries
(EU-ACP), arrived here Wednesday from Frankfurt, Germany, local
Noticias newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After her meeting with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano
Wednesday, Kinnoick said she is collecting data for a report which
will later be the framework for cooperations between European
Union (EU) countries and southern African countries, especially
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The EU is willing to promote its cooperative relations with
southern Africa, said Kinnoick, adding that Mozambique should take
advantage of this willingness to expand cooperation with the EU.
</P>
<P>
Kinnoick mentioned that most of southern Africa used to be the
colonies of European countries, therefore, Europe, as the
so-called "old continent", has the obligation to provide basis for
the security and political, social and economic stability for the
region so that countries in the region could implement their
development programs in a peaceful and harmonious atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
She also pledged that the EU will continue to support the
development programs of Mozambican government and the private
sector, particularly the programs for social development.
</P>
<P>
During her stay in Mozambique, Kinnoick will inspect EU's
health and education development programs in Sofala, Manica and
Zambezia provinces in central Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
She will leave for Zimbabwe after concluding her visit in
Mozambique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
