<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Back Pain May Be Genetic, Study Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Up to 60 percent of back pain
could be caused by faulty genes, a new British study suggests.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at St Thomas' Hospital in London studied 400 set of
twins, and found that identical twins with back problems often
have similar symptoms and worn-out discs in exactly the same
position of the spine.
</P>
<P>
The study, published in the Arthritis and Rheumatism journal,
measured disc degeneration in the neck and lower back with
magnetic resonance imaging scans.
</P>
<P>
The analysis showed genes accounted for about 60 percent of the
risk of developing arthritic discs in the spine.
</P>
<P>
Dr Tim Spector, director of the hospital's Twin Research Unit,
said although occupation, posture and injuries obviously played a
role in some people, the study showed a worn out disc was largely
inherited.
</P>
<P>
More than half the population in Britain are affected by back
and neck pain, which is the commonest cause of time off work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
