<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford Develops World's Smallest Web Server </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Vaughan Pratt, Stanford
professor of computer science, has developed the world's
smallest web server which could be put into pocket and brought
to any where.
</P>
<P>
The matchbox-sized device contains all the hardware and
software needed to operate a web site. It is less than 1 3/4
inches high, 2 3/4 inches wide and 1/4 inch thick. It can
perform all the basic functions of a typical desktop computer
that occupies 3000 times the space.
</P>
<P>
"It is basically a powerful little computer," Pratt says. It
consists of an AMD 486-SX computer with a 66 megahertz central
processing unit, 16 megabytes of random access memory(RAM), and
16 megabytes of flash read-only memory(ROM). It is connected to
the Internet through a parallel port and runs a cut-down version
of linux. Because the machine is a web server, it does not need
a keyboard or a display. It can be operated from another
computer over the web connection.
</P>
<P>
"Put this computer into your shirt pocket, hook it to a
wireless modem, and you could carry it around with you," Pratt says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
