<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Asks for Attention to Older Persons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Thursday called on the world community to act to
meet the long-term needs of older persons, especially older
women and older persons in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in a speech at the opening of a video conference for the
International Year of Older Persons, said that "while this
International year can do a great deal in terms of raising
awareness, building coalition and mobilization both resources and
political will, we must also recognize the need to plan for the
long-term."
</P>
<P>
On the situation of older woman, the U.N. chief said, "Women
comprise the majority of older persons in all but a few countries.
They are more likely than men to be poorer in old ages, and more
likely to face discrimination."
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, their contributions as care-givers -- for example,
to grandchildren orphaned by AIDS -- are often overlooked and
unpaid, if paid at all," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
On the situation of developing countries, he said, "All
societies coping with the graying of their societies will have to
set aside substantial resources, and ensure that public health
and social services are up to the task."
</P>
<P>
He said that "developing nations, where the majority of older
persons live, will continue to need international help and
solidarity."
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, "in something of a paradox, the new longevity
requires wiser investments in their earlier phases of life in
childhood, youth and mid-life. This will contribute to healthy
life-styles and life-long learning and all the other pillars of an
active old age."
</P>
<P>
The year 1999 was designated by the General Assembly as the
International Year of Older Persons in a bid to bring
international and national attention to the needs of older persons
in all societies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
