<HEADLINE> Spain Promises to Deter Kurdish Activities: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit said Thursday that his Spanish counterpart Jose Maria Aznar
had assured him of deterring a meeting of the so-called "Kurdish
parliament in exile" in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that he had a telephone conversations with Aznar
Wednesday night, in which the Spanish prime minister promised to
make efforts and continue to do so in the future to deter the
decision of the Basque parliament to allow the Kurdish body to
hold a meeting in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, Ecevit noted that "Aznar said that they can not
intervene with the internal affairs of the Basque region as it is
one of the autonomous regions in Spain."
</P>
<P>
The "Kurdish parliament in exile" is regarded by Ankara as a
wing of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been
fighting since 1984 a guerrilla war for an independent Kurdish
state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts between the PKK and the Turkish security forces
have claimed at least 37,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Aznar stressed that they will make great efforts to prevent the
deterioration of the ties between Turkey and Spain, said Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit pointed out that if the Basque parliament opens its
doors to the so-called "Kurdish parliament in exile," this will
be a "very dangerous behavior."
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Spanish government will not give
opportunity to the deterioration of the Turkish-Spanish ties due
to the "Kurdish parliament in exile." 
</P>
</TEXT>
