<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Tourism Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Tourism in South Africa
has experienced a quantum leap in growth in the recent five years,
and the country has topped Africa's tourist destinations, South
African Tourism Minister Pallo Jordan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South Africa ranks 25th in the World Tourism Organization's
(WTO) listing of the world's 40 top holiday destinations, Jordan
said at a media briefing in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
WTO figures show that South Africa is currently among the seven
 countries in the world which has seen its tourism industry
growing at a rate of over 10 percent in the past three years,
Jordan was quoted by South African Press Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, crimes against tourists remain a big threat to tourism
and has the potential to cripple opportunities in the industry, he
said.
</P>
<P>
More than 5.9 million tourists visited South Africa last year,
an increase of 10 percent on the 1997 figure, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
The industry contributed 53.2 billion Rand (8.9 billion U.S.
Dollars) toward total gross domestic product (GDP) in 1998, which
is 8.2 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Tourism has created 187,000 new jobs in the country in the past
three years, bringing the total of jobs in the industry to 7.4
million, which represents seven percent of the country's total
employment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan expressed concern for the high level of crime in South
Africa, saying the recent spate of bombings in Cape Town, one of
the favorite destinations for foreign visitors, had a very
negative effect on the country's image abroad.
</P>
<P>
To counter the problem, the Tourism Department has established
a tourism safety task group, which involves the police, to ensure
that tourists are safe in the country, Jordan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
