<HEADLINE> Impact of Euro on Africa Unlikely to Be Huge: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean business people were
told Thursday the newly introduced Euro currency is unlikely to
have a huge impact on Africa as the level of trade with the
European Monetary Union (EMU) is still low.
</P>
<P>
Economic adviser of the European Commission Jose Leandro told a
high level luncheon of Zimbabwe business people that the effect
would depend on the extend to which the Euro will increase or
reduce exchange rate volatility between the main international
currencies, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"This means that the effect on Africa will be small and will
take time to filter through," Leandro said.
</P>
<P>
The international impact of the Euro would be primarily felt in
 countries with close trading and economic links like the three
sub-groups of the French Franc area in Africa, countries of the
Mediterranean as well as those of central and eastern Europe,
Leandro said.
</P>
<P>
The rest of Africa was likely to see the effect of trade
creation in Europe resulting from positive macro- and
micro-economic factors of reduced interest rates and the
efficiency gains of using one monetary system.
</P>
<P>
"Our studies have shown that the trade creation factor is
higher than the trade diversion factor, so there is anticipated
rise in import demand," Leandro said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
