<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Warns of Continued Threats to Tiger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Marking the end of the Chinese
Year of the Tiger, the conservation organization WWF warned on
Thursday that despite sustained efforts over the past year, much
remains to be done to prevent the tiger from becoming extinct
early next century.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot let up for one moment if we are to ensure that
tigers will still exist in the wild by the next Chinese Year of
the Tiger in 2010," said Elizabeth Kemf, Species Conservation
Information Manager at the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF).
</P>
<P>
In its latest study Wanted Alive: Tigers in the Wild published
here Thursday, the WWF said that while significant legislative
progress has been made over the past year, unless efforts continue
to eliminate the demand for tiger products, and to reinforce
anti-poaching measures, this magnificent feline will be stalked
into extinction.
</P>
<P>
"The tiger is threatened almost exclusively by human action,
and unless governments and other decision makers take the
necessary steps, the efforts of the conservation community can
only have a delaying effect on the decline of the tiger," said
Kemf, one of the authors of the WWF report.
</P>
<P>
Tiger numbers have declined by a dramatic 95 percent over the
past 100 years. Three of the eight subspecies of tiger, the bali,
Caspian and Javan tigers have become extinct. The South China
tiger risks the same fate as only 20 or 30 are known to remain in
the wild, down from an estimated 4,000 in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
The world tiger population is estimated to be between 5,000 and
7,200 now. Major threats to the tiger include illegal hunting for
the medicinal trade, loss of prey species, weak law enforcement,
poaching, habitat loss as well as a shrinking gene pool.
</P>
<P>
The WWF has called 1998 the Year for the Tiger. The
above-mentioned threats were addressed through a range of
different activities. These included establishing a Tiger
Emergency Fund, supporting the tiger Conservation Program in
India, and work in the Russian Far East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
