<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Participants to a World Trade
Organization (WTO) pact to liberalize the financial services
sector have put off their decision on the implementation date till
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting had been set for February 11 but missions of some of
the 54 participants who have ratified the pact indicated they
might not have received final instructions in time from their
capitals, said trade officials here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 54 are expected to agree to implement the deal, which
covers banking, insurance and related sectors, from March 1 as
originally planned.
</P>
<P>
Another 17 participants, including major players like
Australia, Brazil and Luxemburg, who signed the deal in December
1997 have not yet completed ratification procedures, which were
due to have been over by the end of January. They are expected to
be given an extension. 
