<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Resolves Rift Between Executive, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The meeting between the
Zimbabwean government and representatives from the Law Society
Council of Zimbabwe (LSCZ) Thursday agreed the apparent rift
between the executive and the judiciary was on matters of
procedure and approach.
</P>
<P>
Justice, Legal and Parliamentary Affairs Minister Emmerson
Mnangagwa attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Law Society President Canaan Dube told
reporters that the meeting agreed the rift centered mainly on the
need by each arm of the government to recognize and respect the
different roles they played in terms of the constitution, the
Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held against the backlash of three Supreme
Court judges by President Robert Mugabe last weekend over a
petition in which they asked him to reaffirm the government still
recognize the rule of law in the country following the arrest of
two journalists by the military police and their subsequent
alleged torture.
</P>
<P>
The two journalists were arrested over a story of a failed coup
attempt and the government ignored three court orders to release
the reporters resulting in the petition.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting was cordial, fruitful and constructive and at this
historic meeting, it was considered to be common cause that the
executive arm of government upholds, protects and respects, as
before and always, the rule of law, court orders and the
independence of the judiciary," Dube said.
</P>
<P>
"The Law Society of Zimbabwe is, therefore, confident that the
apparent differences of opinion between the executive and the
judiciary, albeit on procedural issues, can and will be resolved
without delay," Dube said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
