<HEADLINE> PNA Considering Put-off of Statehood Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat said Thursday that the
Palestinians are considering put-off of statehood declaration.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came amid wide speculation that Arafat is likely to
put off statehood declaration in order not to be made a issue by
hard-line Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu in the May
elections, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has repeatedly said that he will declare an independent
state on May 4, the deadline by which Israel and the Palestinians
are supposed to have reached a permanent agreement according to
the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
But he has been under mounting pressure to postpone such a
declaration since Israel's parliament decided last month to hold
elections two weeks after the Oslo deadline.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the U.S. and the European Union have tried to convince
the Palestinian leader that a unilateral declaration on May 4 will
drive jittering Israeli voters to elect a hard-line party to power.
</P>
<P>
Reports have emerged recently that Arafat is considering to
delay the statehood announcement until December 31 if Washington
backs the new date.
</P>
<P>
A famous strategic think tank in Israel, the Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center for Strategic Study, submitted a report
to Netanyahu earlier this week, saying that Arafat might postpone
his statehood plan if Washington agrees to pressure Israel to move
forward the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu still used his opportunity of meeting with visiting
Belgian Deputy Prime Minister Elio Di Rupo Thursday to renew his
warning that a unilateral declaration will be total violations of
signed agreements between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
His government has threatened to annex parts of the West Bank
still under its control if the Palestinians unilaterally declare
the statehood on May 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
