<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Trade Growth Continues to Slow in 1998: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s
trade growth in 1998 saw a gradual slowdown despite a total
surplus of 88 billion U.S. dollars for January-October period,
EU's official statistical report published on Thursday shows.
</P>
<P>
The 11-nation euro zone had a trade surplus with the rest of
the world of 8.2 billion U.S. dollars in October. This gave euro
zone a total surplus of 88 billion U.S. dollars for
January-October, down 0.68 billion U.S. dollars compared with the
same period in 1997, said the Eurostat, the EU statistical office.
</P>
<P>
The euro-zone's extra-trade with the outside world includes
trade with four member states not adopting the euro, namely the
Britain, Sweden, Denmark and Greece. Currently, EU's intra-trade
accounts for about 75 percent of its total trade volume.
</P>
<P>
In October 1998, 15 EU member countries had a trade surplus of
1.82 billion U.S. dollars with the rest of the world. However,
there was a trade surplus of only 18.4 billion U.S. dollars in the
first 10 months compared to 44 billion U.S. dollars in
January-October of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though extra- and intra-trade growth last October showed weak
or falling in both the 11-country euro zone and all the 15-member
EU region, EU as a whole had strong trade growth with the United
States and China in the first 10 months last year.
</P>
<P>
EU trade with the United States was well up in the first 10
months with 14 percent increase for exports and 11 percent gain
for imports over the same period a year earlier, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat also pointed out that effects of the situation in
Asian financial markets can be seen in a fall in exports to Japan
with 14 percent decrease, but trade growth with China remains
strong with 10 percent increase for exports and 13 percent
increase for imports. At the same time, trade with the main
Eastern European partners, namely Poland, Czech Republic and
Hungary, is also growing strongly.
</P>
<P>
In the period of January-October 1998, Germany still enjoyed
the largest surplus with 66.3 billion U.S. dollars, while
Britain's deficit rose strongly to -39.3 billion U.S. dollars. And
Ireland continued to show the strongest growth, and now has the
third highest surplus of 19.2 billion U.S. dollars in
January-October period last year, the Eurostat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
