<HEADLINE> Lebanese President to Visit Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud is to pay a two-day official visit to Syria starting
Friday, his first tour abroad since assuming power last November.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of People radio quoted Presidential Palace sources
as saying the president will hold talks with his Syrian
counterpart Hafez Assad and other senior officials on bilateral
ties and the peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will also focus on the situation in south Lebanon
where Israeli occupation forces and Lebanese guerrillas are locked
in a war of attrition on daily basis.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's resistance movement, spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to
oust Israelis and its allied South Lebanon Army out of the region.
</P>
<P>
The two president are expected to reaffirm the "entwinement of
Lebanese and Syrian tracks" in the peace talks with Israel, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Israel occupies Syria's Golan Heights it captured in the 1967
Middle East War. Peace negotiations between the two sides was
stalled in 1996 when Israel's general elections brought the
right-wing Likud party to power.
</P>
<P>
Syria wants the return of the strategic plateau, as promised in
a tacit agreement with Israel's previous Labor government. The new
Israeli prime minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, however, refused to be
tied to the Labor stance and cede an inch of the land.
</P>
<P>
On the south Lebanon issue, the Jewish state offered last April
to withdraw from the occupied border strip "provided security
arrangements can be reached" with the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
The offer was rejected by Lebanon and its ally Syria, which
asked Israel to exit without any preconditions as demanded by
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Israel accused Syria of holding south Lebanon as a bargaining
chip to seek a full Israeli withdrawal which will also include
the Golan. Syria has 35,000 troops stationed in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, a former army commander, was elected Lebanon's 11th
president apparently enjoying both the approval of Assad and
popular support of the Lebanese people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
