<HEADLINE> Tanzania Passes New Land Acts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's National
Assembly Thursday endorsed the much-awaited Land Bill and the
Village Land Bill, 1999 with the Minister for Lands and Human
Settlement Development Gideon Cheyo calling for an end to land
disputes.
</P>
<P>
Cheyo challenged villages embroiled in the disputes to sit down
and resolve their conflicts before land officers are notified to
mark land borders.
</P>
<P>
He told parliament in the central city of Dodoma that pamphlets
and periodicals will be prepared and distributed in villages to
enlighten people on land ownership rights, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Cheyo said it is untrue that the government has been pressured
by foreign forces to table the bills, insisting that it was
locally conceived.
</P>
<P>
Tabling the bills last Thursday, the minister said his ministry
has made sure that all sections of the act which discriminates
women from men in land acquisition were scrapped.
</P>
<P>
"The rights of women in acquiring, owning and selling land have
been harmonized to equal those of their male counterparts," he
said, adding that the emphasis is to do away with gender
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
Under the bills, investors will have no right on land
ownership, instead they will get land as tenants under special
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Investors will be given land for specific periods depending on
the nature of business they undertake, Cheyo said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said land disputes should be dealt with promptly
before they cause social disharmonization in the society.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Deputy Minister Mudhihiri Mohamed Mudhihiri promised
that land offices in the regions will be provided with essential
equipment and facilities to improve working efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He said functionaries will also attend various courses intended
to sharpen their skills on handling land issues more
intelligently.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the bills were passed, a group of women
members of parliament chanted inside and outside the house chamber
to welcome the act for giving women equal land ownership rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
