<HEADLINE> Dutch Bank Executive Sees Asia Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian economies are
likely to be the first to show signs of recovery, said a Dutch
bank executive said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his investment outlook to reporters in Geneva, Jacob
van Duijn, head of investment operations for Dutch bank Robeco,
said that the Asian economies would be first out of difficulties
as they were first to run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
Van Duijn said Robeco, which puts the value of assets under its
management at 80 billion euros was now putting more money into
equity markets such as Hong Kong and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Van Duijn predicted that the global economy
would slow down and would not bottom out until the second half of
the next year.
</P>
<P>
He said his views were based on a cyclical outlook. "Every
seven to 11 years there is a recession," he said, noting the last
world recession was in 1991-92.
</P>
<P>
"We're really headed for a global economic slowdown," he said.
"If everything stays normal, then a cyclical low could be reached
in the second half of the year 2000."
</P>
<P>
Last year's economic turmoil in southeast Asia had prompted
companies there to restructure and many had also gained a
competitive advantage for export through the currency devaluations
which were part of the upheaval, Van Duijn said.
</P>
<P>
Looking further ahead, Van Duijn said a combination of
demographic factors and economic cycles meant the West was likely
to reach full employment around 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
