<HEADLINE> U.N. Launches Project for Int'l Elders Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 11 (Xinhua) -- the United Nations Center for
Human Settlements (UNCHS) Thursday launched a project "Living
conditions of older persons in urban communities" here as a
contribution to the International Year of Older Person 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based UNCHS, also known as Habitat, said in a press
release that the project aims at facilitating field research in a
number of cities in both developed and developing countries and
attaching importance to the urban and housing needs of older
persons.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Toepfer, Acting Executive Director of Habitat, said that
older persons could contribute greatly to the development of
cultural, economic and social activities. Local governments and
municipal authorities should have the greatest responsibility to
develop such innovative mechanisms and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that every month, the world's elderly
population increases by 1.2 million. By 2020, 1.4 billion persons
will be over 60 years, an increase of 240 percent since 1980, with
the fastest growth in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
By 2025, worldwide average life expectancy will reach 73 years,
a 50 percent improvement on the 1955 average of only 48 years. One
in five person will be 60 years or above by 2050, the release
added.
</P>
<P>
Longevity is an indicator of a nation's progress and
development, the release said, adding that ageing population has
posed particular demands on public services, such as housing,
transportation and health facilities.
</P>
<P>
It urged urban planners, housing units, public and private
sectors to suit the needs of the elderly and pay close attention
to the valuable contributions of older persons in the social and
economic development of their communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
