<HEADLINE> Annan Favors Peaceful Settlement to African, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said on Thursday that he favors a diplomatic and
political solution to conflicts in Africa and the Serbian province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Annan made the remarks to reporters shortly after he briefed
the Security Council on the latest development in Sierra Leone,
Congo(K), Congo, the Central African Republic, Angola and the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, where conflicts are raging on.
</P>
<P>
"We did go into the status of these crisis, and we also
discussed the tendencies today in Africa by governments tending
to be relying on military means to solve problems, rather than
political means," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are also concerned about the military adventurism by
governments to cross borders to send troops to fight in one
conflict and the other," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Council is worried about the implications of this
development for the concept of a nation-station the African
continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that the United Nations can play a major
role in the maintenance of peace and security only "when the
parties involved want to make peace, want to settle their
differences."
</P>
<P>
"The inspiration for long-term and viable peace has to spring
from the leader and the people," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the conflict in Congo (K), he said that it is possible that
the United Nations will consider sending peacekeepers into the
African country to "monitor and help the implementation of the
peace agreements."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is supporting regional initiatives to
restore peace in these areas, particularly the efforts by West
African countries to bring peace to Sierra Leone, where
democratically-elected government, headed by President Ahmed
Kabah, is fighting with rebels after they were flushed out of the
capital Freetown by West African peacekeepers, known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
On the conflicts in Kosovo, Annan said that he is "cautiously
optimistic" about the on-going peace talks in France, sponsored
by the six-nation Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
"As long as they are talking, I think we are making progress,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
