<HEADLINE> Romanians to Be Better Shielded Against Deceitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government
adopted Thursday a bill of advertising aiming at a better
protection of consumers, producers, traders and services operators
against deceitful advertising and its negative impact.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, advertising should be decent and correct. The
bill bans cheating or subliminal advertising, that prejudices
respect for human dignity and public moral, takes advantage of
human superstitions, credulity or fear, and encourages the sale of
goods and services infringing the existing legislation.
</P>
<P>
It also forbids tobacco publicity within TV or radio broadcast,
or in the written press, on the first and last cover of the
papers. Tobacco and alcohol advertising is also banned if
addressing minors or present minors consuming them.
</P>
<P>
Alcoholic drinks and tobacco presented as having therapeutic,
stimulating or sedative effects, and cigarettes lacking a
Romanian-language warning on their harmful consequences, are also
forbidden under the bill.
</P>
<P>
Law infringement attracts material and civil penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
