<HEADLINE> Dutch Preparing for Water Management Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands is preparing
for good water management to protect the country against the
danger of flooding due to the combined hazard of rising sea levels
and falling land levels, Dutch Government Information Council said
in the Hague Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Dutch State Secretary for Transport, Public Works and Water
Management Monique de Vries presented Wednesday a policy document
on urban water systems, rivers, coastal waters and the sea. The
state secretary also announced an action program in which
priorities are set for Dutch assistance in water management
projects in other countries.
</P>
<P>
A study is to be carried out into the water management
structure needed in the Netherlands for the 21st century.
According to the study findings, an independent committee will
advise the government on what improvements need to be made, 115
million guilders (59.3 million U.S. dollars) have already been set
aside for cleaning up the beds of water systems, and a further 700
million guilders (360 million dollars) have been reserved for
large-scale wetland projects, including the Rhine-Maas delta and
the Ijsselmeer lake.
</P>
<P>
The council also said the Netherlands is to make extra efforts
to limit flooding and the ensuing damage in the future. Pumping
stations at four strategically important points in the country's
hydromechanical system are to be upgraded. 
</P>
