<HEADLINE> European Major Stock Markets Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON February 11 (Xinhua) - A Strong performance on Wall
Street helped boost shares in European markets Thursday. However,
concerns about the outlook for the euro capped gains.
</P>
<P>
In London, the FTSE 100 closed 118.3 points ahead at 5888.5,
with some 34.5 points accounted for by British Telecom (BT) alone.
</P>
<P>
The telecoms giant added 101p or 11 percent to close at 1009p
as investors were cheered by robust revenue growth, the result of
big turnover gains in mobile, Internet and overseas startup
operations.
</P>
<P>
BT said pre-tax profits in the three months to December 31,
1998, fell to 858 million pounds from 1.019 billion in the same
period last year, but they easily topped forecasts of 698 to 792
million pounds.
</P>
<P>
However, shares are still well short of levels held last week
before succumbing to a string of six consecutive losses. The FTSE
100 finished at 6013 on 2 February.
</P>
<P>
German shares moved further ahead as Wall Street traded in
positive territory, although investors remained wary following
recent volatility.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax closed 55.25 points higher at 4869.29. Dealers
said there was a notable departure of foreign investors in recent
sessions as they grew cautious about the euro's performance on
foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
Paris shares moved ahead, also boosted by positive signals from
New York and a raft of positive earnings news. The Cac 40 finished
70.41 points higher at 4,072.34. 
</P>
</TEXT>
