<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swine Fever Not Found in Ghana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has not yet recorded any
case of the African swine fever which is sweeping across the
continent, Samuel Achaw Ofosu, deputy director of Veterinary
Services, said in Accra Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Samples taken from about 20 percent of the animals reared
along our borders for laboratory analysis show that our animals
have not had the deadly disease," he was quoted by Ghana News
Agency as saying, adding, "We still bleed some animals every now
and then for analysis."
</P>
<P>
Ofosu, however, warned that "since the disease is still in our
neighboring countries, the situation is grave and the whole
sub-region is not free."
</P>
<P>
He advised farmers to look out for symptoms such as red patches
on the skin, high temperature, dragging and paralysis of hind legs
and loss of appetite and report immediately to the nearest
veterinary station or offices of the Ministry of Food and
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The viral disease, which affects only pigs, and has no known
treatment nor vaccine, has reportedly killed about 80 percent of
pigs reared in Lagos, Nigeria, in the past six months. A
committee estimated the financial loss to the farmers at more than
723 million Naira (about 8.4 million Dollars). Similar losses
have been reported across the country, resulting in acute shortage
of pork.
</P>
<P>
Pig farmers in Lagos, Nigeria's economic hub, are threatening
undisclosed action unless government came to their rescue.
</P>
<P>
Ofosu warned that even though the disease cannot be passed on
to human beings, the carcass of an infected animal is unwholesome
and can cause other conditions like food poisoning, and therefore,
it must not be eaten.
</P>
<P>
He said Ghana has placed a ban on the importation of pigs, pork
and pig products from Cote d' Ivoire and Togo, where the disease
has been reported. Such products are, however, not imported from
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The ban is still in force, he said, adding that anybody who
wants to import pigs and pig products must acquire a permit from
the Service.
</P>
<P>
According to Ofosu, Ghana took immediate steps to prevent the
disease from entering its borders when an outbreak was reported in
Cote d' Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The disease was first reported in Cameroun in 1997 where it
became endemic. It later got to Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
Later Benin recorded an outbreak which spread to Togo and
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Following this precarious situation, the Food and Agriculture
Organization sent a consultant from Rome in late 1997 to
investigate the situation and then set up an emergency Technical
Cooperation Program involving 386,000 Dollars for nine countries
in west Africa, including Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, a two-day workshop was organized last
November for veterinary personnel from all over the country on how
to diagnose the disease and how to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
Pork provides a substantial amount of Ghana's animal protein
requirement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
