<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 11 (XInhua) -- The National Council on Women
and Development (NCWD) has condemned the increasing spate of
violence against women in northern Ghana.
</P>
<P>
The council has, therefore, called on the government to revoke
customs, traditions and religious practices which help perpetuate
violence in line with the International Declaration on the
Elimination of Violence Against Women, the Ghana News Agency (GNA)
 reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Tamale, northern Ghana,
Wednesday, Fati Paul, regional coordinator of the NCWD, asked the
law enforcement agencies to conduct thorough investigations into
such incidents.
</P>
<P>
The conference was in reaction to the latest incident involving
the alleged beating to death of a 28-year-old pregnant woman, Fati
Abdallah, by her husband, Abdul Rahman Ziblim, 41, in Tamale.
</P>
<P>
Mariama Sumani, chairperson of the regional planning committee
of the NCWD, said a number of long-term strategies had been
adopted to eliminate violence against women.
</P>
<P>
These include public education to raise the status of women to
gain recognition of their full human rights and lobbying of
parliament to reform laws that allow such violence.
</P>
<P>
Hajia Alima Mahama, a member of the committee, expressed
concern about the growing incidence of lynching of old women on
suspicion that they are witches, rape, child defilement, assault
and female genital mutilation in the region. 
</P>
