<HEADLINE> Israel Raps EU for Opposing Jewish Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
on Thursday criticized European Union (EU) for backing a U.N.
resolution calling Jewish settlement activities in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip a violation of the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's
communication adviser, said that Israel was very upset with the
EU member states' vote for the resolution.
</P>
<P>
He said that the EU members should think about the adverse
effect of the resolution on the peace process before they voted.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly adopted a resolution 115-2 Tuesday
night, calling for a meeting of the signatories to the 1949 Fourth
Geneva Convention to be held this summer to consider measures to
enforce the convention "in the occupied Palestinian territory,
including Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, who arrived in Israel
Wednesday on his first official visit, bore the brunt of Israel's
displeasure.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Netanyahu moved his mid-morning meeting with
Fischer to the evening, citing that he had to cope with a brewing
domestic crisis with the country's powerful ultra-Orthodox
minority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon canceled his talks
with Fischer, saying doctors ordered him to rest at home because
of knee injury he sustained in a car accident early this week.
</P>
<P>
But Bar-Illan insisted that there was no link between Israel's
displeasure with the EU and the sudden schedule changes.
</P>
<P>
"Fischer's visit is very welcome. Fischer has made some
statements favorable (to Israel)," Bar-Illan said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Jerusalem Post reported Thursday that Israeli
Foreign Ministry was in private blaming Germany, which is holding
the rotating six-month EU presidency, for not doing more to thwart
the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Fischer will go on to Gaza for talks with Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat after visit to Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
