<HEADLINE> Egypt, Iraq Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Iraq have signed an
agreement to export 86 million U.S. dollars worth of food to Iraq,
Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammad Mahdi Saleh said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Saleh made the remarks during his visit to the Egyptian
Governorate of Daqahliya in the Nile Delta, 90 kilometers north of
Cairo. But he did not say when the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
The volume of trade exchange between the two countries climbed
to 300 million dollars in 1997 from 20 millions dollars in earlier
years, the Iraqi official was quoted by Egypt's Middle East News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is under economic sanctions, barring it from trading with
other countries, which were imposed in 1990 by the United Nations
Security Council after its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
But the 1996 oil-for-food agreement reached between the U.N.
and Iraq allows it to sell a limited amount of oil to buy food and
medicine for its people.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is one of the major exporters to Iraq. Its exports of
food to the country are secured under the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister underlined that the high mortality rate of
the Iraqi children and elderly each month is part of the
repercussions of the U.N. economic embargo.
</P>
<P>
Official figures of Iraq have showed that hundreds of children
and elderly in the country die every month due to shortage of food
and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official said that exports of Arab countries to Iraq
have accounted for 50 percent of his country's imports.
</P>
<P>
Inter-arab trade exchange stands at a mere 10 percent of the
total volume of Arab foreign trade, Saleh stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister, accompanied by Daqahliya Governor Fakhr
al-Din Khaled, paid a visit to a number of production and
industrial facilities in the governorate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
