<HEADLINE> Clinton Hosts "Informal Visit" With Schroeder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton on
Thursday hosted an "informal visit" with German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"This is an informal visit," he told reporters, explaining that
in the diplomatic language of Washington it fell below the
no-frills "working visit" stature -- which avoids any hint of
pomp.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said that during the two-hour get-together, which
included lunch, Clinton and his guest were "to spend some time on
the upcoming NATO summit which we will host in April and the G-8
meeting which the Germans will host in June."
</P>
<P>
Washington will be the site of a 50th anniversary celebration
of the NATO alliance, while Cologne will host the annual meeting
of the seven major industrial nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has said he want the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization to reconsider its long-standing "first strike"
doctrine on nuclear weapons, which he views as an unnecessary
relic of the Cold War, but his position was greeted with rejection
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
Administration officials said the meeting between Clinton and
Schroeder was designed in part oto develop a working relationship
between them.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl once developed
a relationship by going out to restaurants together and feasting,
and the president "wants a relationship with Schroeder as well,"
said one of the administration officials in describing the purpose
of the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
