<HEADLINE> Zambia's Economy to Perform Well in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- This year will be the turning
point for Zambia's economy because basic indicators have suggested
that the economy will perform well, Jacob Mwanza, governor of the
country's central bank, said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He made the prediction at a luncheon held for media heads and
senior management of the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He said last year's economic decline will be reversed this year
because more investment and more donor support is coming to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Last year the economy did not do well due to various factors
like the poor performance of the mines, poor price of copper and
poor performance of the agricultural sector, said the governor.
</P>
<P>
He also blamed the lack of balance of payment support and
business confidence as well as the delayed sale of copper mines of
the Zambia Consolidate Copper Mines (ZCCM), for the poor economic
performance in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"We have this year set ourselves goals like bringing inflation
to 15 percent which we hope we will accomplish because the basic
indicators have suggested that the economy will perform well," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the governor, Zambia has reached an agreement in
the balance of payment support which has started to flow while the
 privatization of ZCCM has reached an irreversible stage.
</P>
<P>
"The rains this season have been good and favorable because it
is our wish not to import more grain to feed the population," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that this year's budget report allocates 37 percent of
the government spending to capital expenditure is a good sign for
growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
Most important areas like infrastructure construction will be
tackled which will see roads rehabilitated, education and energy
receiving priority, he said.
</P>
<P>
"All these plus other investment opportunities which stalled
over a period of the time due to slow race in the privatization of
the mines make us feel that our targets are achievable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have in the past two weeks infused in the economy 18.8
million U.S. Dollars to stabilize the economy. Last Tuesday we
put in 9.3 million Dollars and this week we put in 9.5 million
Dollars," Mwanza said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
