<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Private Businessman Gets His Day In Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese private businessman
who was charged with misuse of public property was declared
innocent on Thursday after a lengthy court debate.
</P>
<P>
The businessman, Zhang Xiaojing, 58, had founded a factory in
1987 in the city of Dalian at a time when there were no
regulations on registering private businesses in China and he had
to register the plant in the name of a collectively owned factory.
</P>
<P>
But, in 1995, when he established a privately owned company and
transferred the old factory's property and debts to the new one,
the local procurators decided to prosecute him.
</P>
<P>
According to their accusation, Zhang was guilty of embezzlement
of public property and, in 1998, he was sentenced to 3 year in
prison, with a 5-year reprieve and he appealed the sentence at the
Dalian Intermediate People's Court.
</P>
<P>
That lead to a year-long debate, with some people saying that
Zhang had eaten up public property because his old plant was
registered under a collectively-owned factory, while others said
that Zhang was innocent because he built the plant with his own
investment and paid all his own debts.
</P>
<P>
After a lengthy investigation, the court decided that Zhang's
company was a privately owned one in every sense and that the
first verdict against Zhang needed to be recalled.
</P>
<P>
This mistake arose out of a lack of laws and regulations
protecting private entrepreneurs' rights in 1995, Zhang's counsel
said, explaining that, before 1988, when China passed its
Provisional Regulation on Private Enterprises, the growing number
of private companies and factories had to put themselves under
government departments or state-owned enterprises to receive legal
protection.
</P>
<P>
But, as more and more bosses realized in the 1990s that they
actually own the companies and factories, they began to ask for
change of ownership.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Chinese government decided to re-define ownership
of thousands of factories, opening a new chapter in the history of
private enterprises. But this proved to be not such an easy job,
as Wang Shuxiang, the chief justice who handled Zhang's case
explains, because the line between state enterprise and private
company was often blurred due to a lack of evidence and the
ambiguity of the regulations.
</P>
<P>
In northern China, where Dalian is located and where state
enterprises are plentiful, a private businessperson could find it
really hard to win a lawsuit, when compared to southern coastal
provinces, where private industry is commonplace, said Liu
Zhongquan, a professor at Dalian Science and Engineering
University.
</P>
<P>
"Zhang's victory is the victory of the socialist market, which
is gradually maturing, and it indicates a more important role of
private entrepreneurs in rejuvenating the nation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Chinese Communist Party has proposed Constitutional
amendments that could place the private sector in a much higher
position, but, as for now, Zhang said, "I believe the law is just.
Private enterprises will get a more fair development environment
as the legal system is improved."  
</P>
</TEXT>
