<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRC Continues Humanitarian Operations in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) has recently carried out a seeds program in
Somalia aiming at assisting 15,000 families of small-scale
farmers affected by flooding, Michel Dufour, head of Somalia
delegation in Nairobi, said in a release available here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dufour said the seeds had already been handed out to farmers in
Marere, Jilib, Jamame, Buale, Lower and Middle Shabelle regions in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Concerned by reports that the humanitarian situation for the
most vulnerable Somalia has deteriorated, Dufour stressed that
the ICRC is constantly monitoring the humanitarian situation
there.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, the ICRC has also sent non-food items
such as tarpaulins, blankets and kangas to 1,450 families in
Jilib, Lower and Middle Shabelle regions in southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC is now distributing shelter materials, kangas and
cloths to 500 displaced families in South Mogadishu whose huts
were destroyed in fire.
</P>
<P>
Having reduced its activities last April following a security
incident, the ICRC resumed its field activities last December,
and provided medicines and surgical kits for the war-wounded who
were transferred to the Somalia Red Crescent health centers in
Jamame, Buale, Mugambo,Jilib or to other private hospitals in the
capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Dufour said security is an essential aspect of any ICRC action
and the ICRC did not believe that the general security situation
in Somalia improved during 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the ICRC head noted that in 1999 the ICRC would
continue to operate in Somalia as it does in other context, but
with a constant and close attention to the security situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
