<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Inventories Hold Steady in December as Sales Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- U.S. inventories at
businesses have remained unchanged in December while sales
increase, the Commerce Department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
That means backlogs of unsold goods were relatively lean
heading into 1999. Too big a buildup can cause production cutbacks
as businesses work to sell surplus goods.
</P>
<P>
Inventories held at a seasonally adjusted 1.09 trillion U.S.
dollars in December, the first month with no increase since last
July.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, sales rose 1 percent, the biggest jump since
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
As a result, there were enough goods on shelves and backlots in
December to meet demand for just 1.37 months at the current sales
pace -- a low hit only twice before since 1980.
</P>
<P>
At retailers, inventories rose 0.7 percent and sales rose 1
percent, and at wholesalers, inventories rose 0.5 percent and
sales rose 1.2 percent. Manufacturers' inventories dropped 0.9
percent, in line with an identical 0.9 percent rise in sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
