<HEADLINE> IFAB to Crack Down on cheating at Annual General Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Football
Association Board (IFAB) Annual General Meeting will try to find
ways to expose attempts to deceive the referee when it meets near
Cardiff of the United Kingdom on February 20.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of the IFAB, composed of the Federation
Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) and the four British
national associations, England, Scotland, Wales and Northern
Ireland, will focus on a number of proposed amendments and
additions to the Laws of the Game.
</P>
<P>
These initiatives reflect FIFA's resolve to keep the field of
play free of advertising and to crack down on cheating, FIFA said
in a press release on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed modifications, any simulating action
anywhere on the field would be deemed unsporting behavior and
would be punished by a yellow card.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the participants will also discuss a possible
experiment with two referees and the feasibility of introducing
goal-line technology.
</P>
<P>
Other items for discussion include the possibility of extending
the responsibilities of the fourth official and an evaluation of
experiments currently being conducted on the Laws of the Game.
</P>
</TEXT>
