<HEADLINE> Taliban Deny ceasefire Agreement with Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 12 (Xinhua) - The Afghan Taliban militia
Friday denied reports that they have struck a ceasefire accord
with their rivals.
</P>
<P>
There was no ceasefire agreement in the Ashgabad talks.
However, the two sides agreed on the exchange of prisoners,
Taliban sources here said.
</P>
<P>
Senior Taliban officials and representatives of the opposition
commander, Ahmed Shah Masood, held talks in Turkmenistan on
Wednesday under the aegis of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Maulvi Abdur Rahman Zahid, a senior Taliban official for
foreign affairs, led the Taliban team in the talks while Abdul
Karim Hashmi and Amrullah Saleh represented opposition commander
Masood.
</P>
<P>
It was the first high-level face-to-face meeting between the
two warring Afghan factions after the collapse of their talks in
Islamabad in May last year. The five-day talks in Islamabad had
failed to produce any result.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban, controlling 90 percent of the Afghan territory,
have been under tremendous pressure to begin talks with the
opposition and find out a negotiated settlement of the
long-standing crisis in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban had been declining dialogue with their
foes.
</P>
<P>
The two warring Afghan factions discussed procedure for the
exchange of the prisoners and agreed to hand over lists of their
prisoners to each other.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here believe that isolation of the Taliban in the
world community and continued pressure forced the hard-line
Islamic militia to enter into dialogue with their rivals.
</P>
<P>
They said that the latest meeting between the Taliban and the
opposition was aimed at creating understanding on various issues
before the forthcoming meeting of the Six Plus Two (Afghanistan's
six immediate neighbors plus the U.S. and Russia) in Tashkent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taliban delegation met with Turkmenistan's
Foreign Minister Sheikh Boris Muradov and discussed bilateral
issues, focusing on promotion of trade ties between the two
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
