<HEADLINE> EDS-repeats with correction of figures in Para 4 World Patent Registration Sets New Record in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Intellectual Property
Organization (WIPO) received 67,007 international patent
applications from all over the world in 1998, representing a 23.1
percent increase over 1997, WIPO head said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The rate of growth in the use of the PCT (Patent Cooperation
Treaty) system in 1998 is very promising," said WIPO Director
General Kamil Idris. "This positive trend suggests that users are
increasingly recognizing the advantages the PCT system offers to
them in seeking patent protection in a large number of countries."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Idris called on all PCT members, in
particular developing countries, to take advantage of this unique
system that allows an applicant to seek patent protection in any
of the 98 member countries of the PCT through the filing of a
single "international" application.
</P>
<P>
According to WTPO's revised statistics released on Friday
afternoon, inventors in the United States continued to be the
biggest user of the PCT in 1998, with 42.3 percent of all
applications, followed by their counterparts in Germany (13.6
percent, Japan (9.1 percent), United Kingdom (6.5 percent) and
France (5.0 percent).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, WIPO statistics demonstrate growing use of the PCT
by several developing countries. In 1998, Azerbaijan, Vietnam, and
Zimbabwe began to use the system for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Cuba, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Indonesia, Mexico,
Poland, Romania, Slovakia, Turkey, Ukraine and Uzbekistan made
greater use of the PCT, according to the statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
