<HEADLINE> Action Against Alleged Bribery Officials Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Friday it is premature to take action against
officials who have been linked to a reported 75,000-U.S.-dollar
bribery attempt without solid evidence.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he has full trust and confidence in
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora and Budget and Management
Secretary Benjamin Diokno.
</P>
<P>
"I have not accepted any resignation letter ... I believe we
have to go deeper and find out who is the real culprit," Estrada
said.
</P>
<P>
An earlier report quoted Santiago Toledo, director of the
National Bureau of Investigation, as saying that a businesswoman
last month delivered a package containing 3 million pesos (75,000
U.S. dollars) to the office of Benjamin Diokno.
</P>
<P>
The woman later claimed in her sworn affidavit that the money
was intended to the government's Deputy Executive Secretary
Vicente de la Serna and his executive assistant Ricardo Fulgencio,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The bribery attempt was linked to a deal of 200 million pesos
(5 million U.S. dollars) with the Department of Education, Culture
and Sports, the report said. 
