<P>
SHANGHAI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial and commercial city, plans to build in May an imitation
of an old street this year to highlight its 700 year old history
and culture.
</P>
<P>
The 825 meter-long street, to be located in the famous Yuyuan
Commercial and Tourist Zone in downtown Shanghai, will be lined
with more than 100 specialty stores, workshops and cultural and
recreational facilities modeled on the style of the Ming (1368-
1644) and Qing (1633-1911) dynasties.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is one of the country's oldest commercial cities,
boasting many well-known businesses and buildings with unique
characteristics of their own. Yet there has been a tendency in
recent years for them to be replaced by modern shopping centers
and new high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
According to a local government official, such businesses as
pottery workshops, teahouses and bean curd workshops are to be set
up along the western section of the street, aiming to make a
showcase of various past local trades.
</P>
<P>
The eastern section will mainly be reserved for famous shops
from other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
A theater and an outdoor stage for presenting local opera
performances will also be constructed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Outlines Measures on Patent Protection Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
here on Friday that it has outlined a series of concrete measures
to improve the framework for obtaining patent protection in the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body said these measures will include a
proposal for establishing a unitary EU protection of inventions
related to computer programs, an policy document on freedom of
establishment and freedom to provide services for patent agents
and a pilot project to support efforts by national patent offices
to promote innovation.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner for the single market Mario Monti said that this
coherent policy framework lays the foundations for ensuring that
pan-EU patent protection can be obtained more easily than at
present.
</P>
<P>
"This will serve to promote investment in innovation, which is
so crucial to employment, growth and competitiveness in the EU,"
Monti said.
</P>
<P>
"We have made the introduction of a unitary patent valid
throughout the single market a political priority in accordance
with the clearly expressed demands of users and of the European
Parliament for adequate protection at a reasonable cost and with
optimum legal certainty."
</P>
<P>
Other additional measures will result in a substantial
improvement in the EU's patent system to the benefit of innovative
European businesses, said the commissioner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
