<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz Calls for Resolving "Fundamental Differences" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pak-Indian relations
will remain stunted unless India demonstrates its willingness to
work for the resolution of "fundamental differences" between the
two countries, Pakistan Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz Friday.
</P>
<P>
India must go beyond its present emphasis on the peripheral
areas of bilateral relations. "The confidence building measures
are not an end in itself," Aziz said at a luncheon he hosted in
honor of the participants at the first ever Indo-Pak Parliamentary
Conference.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 members of parliament from India and Pakistan are
here to participate in the two-day event, an unofficial Indo-Pak
parliamentary conference which began Friday.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said, sans progress on the core issue of Kashmir, the
Indo-Pak relations will continue to be plagued by mutual mistrust
and suspicion. This will inhibit normalization and growth in their
bilateral relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Unless, we can move towards a settlement of the Kashmir
dispute on the basis of respect for the inherent right of
self-determination of the Kashmiri people, peace will continue to
elude South Asia. This is the obvious lesson of the last 50 years.
There is no escape from this fact," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the Kashmir dispute was a nuclear flashpoint and
it must be settled in accordance with the wishes of Kashmiris.
</P>
<P>
He said that for too long India and Pakistan have been engaged
in an unproductive arms race at the cost of the economic
prosperity and development of the common men in both countries.
"This cycle needs to be broken," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said, Pakistan, was committed to continuing dialogue with
India in its desire to find just solutions to all outstanding
issues between the two countries, including Jammu and Kashmir and
the issues related to regional peace and security.
</P>
<P>
In the present nuclearized environment, tensions and
hostilities carry even greater risks both for Pakistan and India
as well as the region and beyond, said Aziz, adding that "the
current situation, if allowed to drift, is fraught with many
dangers."
</P>
<P>
He also said that Pakistan would like to see a vibrant India
engaged in mutually beneficial cooperation with all its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see a south Asia that is free of poverty and
economic deprivation," Aziz said. "South Asia can become a major
new destination for foreign investment in what observers called
the `Fourth Wave' of the Asian miracle."
</P>
<P>
"But to take full advantage of these opportunities, we have to
improve the security environment of the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister urged Indian members of parliament to make
important contributions to ensure that the present Pak-India
bilateral process does not relapse into a dialogue for the sake of
dialogue.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
