<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, Indian Lawmakers Call for Negotiated Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers of Pakistan and
India Friday called for a negotiated settlement of bilateral
disputes between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They made the call at the first Indo-Pak Parliamentary
Conference which started here Friday and was attended by about 100
delegates from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Problems could not be solved through use of force," said Ehali
Bakhsh Soomro, Speaker of Pakistan's National Assembly, stressing
the need for the settlement of disputes through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Indian delegation Balram Jakbar said that the two
countries should avoid bloodshed and settle differences through
talks, saying "we should talk against war and for the promotion of
peace."
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Minister for Parliamentary Affairs Yasin Khan Watto
reiterated Pakistan's call for the peaceful solution to the
Kashmir issue, saying that without the settlement of the core
issue, the goal of progress in other fields could not be achieved.
</P>
<P>
However, the Indian members of parliament called for settlement
of minor issues first to create better environment for
negotiations on key disputes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the lawmakers from both countries lauded what they
called genuine efforts by the two governments to improve relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They welcomed the Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee's
forthcoming visit to Pakistan on February 20 and the proposed bus
service from New Delhi to Pakistan's second biggest city of
Lahore.
</P>
<P>
They hoped that these measures will reduce tension between the
two countries and result in better mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Some 35 lawmakers members from the two houses of the Indian
parliament, including those from the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party
and the main opposition Congress Party, and more than 60 members
from all the parties in the Pakistani parliament are participating
the two-day conference aiming at giving impetus "towards detente
in the sub-continent."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Resume Land Sales in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will resume its
land sales beginning April this year after suspending them for 10
months, a government official announced here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government will implement a one-year Land Sales Program
from April 1999 to March 2000 and a four-year Land Development
Program from April 2000 to March 2004.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Siu Kwing-chue, secretary for Planning, Environment and
Land, said: "Our policy objective is to ensure stability in the
property market and to provide sufficient land to meet our long
term needs."
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference that this will be achieved by
introducing a modest Land Sale Program for 1999-2000, coupled with
a new "Application System" whereby developers may apply for sale
of sites from a "reserve list."
</P>
<P>
"The flexibility offered by this new mechanism will enable us
to respond to market demand while maintaining overall stability,"
Siu said.
</P>
<P>
"The combination of sites in the reserve list with a regular
land auction and tender program enables the market to decide the
optimum amount of land to be made available for disposal and the
timing for releasing additional land," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
From April 1, 1999 to March 31, 2000, auctions and tenders will
be conducted in accordance with a sale timetable for individual
sites occupying a total of 14 hectares of land for private housing,
15 hectares for the Private Sector Participation scheme and two
hectares for non-housing uses.
</P>
<P>
Under the application system, a developer who is interested in
any site on the reserve list may apply to the government and offer
a minimum price.
</P>
<P>
If the government considers the price reasonable, it will put
up the site for sale by public auction or tender as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The amount of land available for sale under the Application
System includes 22 hectares for private housing and 11 hectares
for non-housing uses.
</P>
<P>
"The government remains committed to its public housing program
of an average of 50,000 units per year and will continue to
develop land for this purpose," Siu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
