<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Getting To Know A New Madam Curie On Chinese Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Marie Curie, the Polish Nobel
Prize winner, will appear on the Chinese stage this April, but
with a new image in a French comedy.
</P>
<P>
The comedy, "The Palm of Mr.Schutz", written by Jean Noel
Fenwick in 1989, which won 4 Moliere Awards the following year and
has been performed more than 2,000 times in 17 countries, will be
performed by a cast from the Chinese Youth Art Theater.
</P>
<P>
The play's Chinese director, Wei Xiaoping, a graduate of China'
s Central Drama Institute who studied in France, was impressed by
the new image the play gave of Marie Curie who has been
stereotyped in textbooks as a woman who cared for nothing but
science and he decided to translate the play, along with his
French wife Pascale Wei.
</P>
<P>
The comedy is based on some Pierre and Marie Curie anecdotes,
with artistic touches added. Marie Curie totally removes her mask
of seriousness and steps off the pedestal down into the mundane
world, according to Wei.
</P>
<P>
This Mme. Curie often jests with her future husband, Pierre,
who initially avoided women in his life but was overcome by this
playful, intelligent, and persevering girl student. They go to the
theater, concerts, and the countryside where they can enjoy
culture and nature in the little time they have and they deal with
obstacles in the path to their discovery of radium.
</P>
<P>
Wei once talked with the French playwright about Marie Curie's
image, a woman who could have been more vivid portrayed. Devoting
one's life to science doesn't mean denying joy in life and, in
fact, a great scientist could possibly cherish life more than
anyone else precisely because the free time is so precious,
something that is conveyed by the play.
</P>
<P>
The cast includes some of the most brilliant names in Chinese
theater. The play will start at Beijing's Chang'an Theater on
April 9.
</P>
<P>
France's Curie and Joliot-Curie Association has offered more
than 50 photos from the family album to be used in the theater.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
