<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Seeks Revision of National Security Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's ruling National
Congress for New Politics (NCNP) Friday said it plans to consult
with the government about the National Security Law, which
concerns South Koreans' contact with Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
"We are planning to hold a consultative meeting with the
government in March or April to revise the law by June," said a
senior NCNP official Friday.
</P>
<P>
NCNP Acting President Cho Se-hyung reported the plan to
President Kim Dae-jung when he met Kim for weekly party affairs
Thursday, said the official.
</P>
<P>
However, the NCNP will make a final decision on whether or not
to revise the law after consulting with its coalition partner, the
United Liberal Democrats (ULD), the official said.
</P>
<P>
The security law, which was passed in 1948 and revised several
times thereafter, bans South Koreans from making unauthorized
contact with Koreans in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party is expected to seek revision of, among other
things, article seven, under which a person could be sentenced to
up to seven years in prison when convicted of praising an anti-
state organization.
</P>
<P>
Observers said the article has often been abused by law-
enforcement authorities to suppress dissidents or political
activities.
</P>
<P>
President Kim has in the past vowed to replace the security law
with a new act on the "defense of the democratic order".
</P>
<P>
The revision plan is expected to meet strong objection not only
from the opposition Grand National Party, but also from the
coalition partner, ULD, said analysts.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
