<HEADLINE> Iraqi Civilian Killed in U.S. Missile Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi civilian was killed
and tens of others injured on Friday during U.S. missile attacks
on civilian targets in northern Iraq, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman was quoted by the Iraqi News Agency INA as saying
that nine formations of U.S. warplanes from a Turkish military
base violated Iraq's northern airspace Friday morning and launched
missiles at the Iraqi air defense sites in Dohuk province and
north Mosul.
</P>
<P>
Since late last month when U.S.-British warplanes bombarded
residential quarters in southern Iraq's Basra province till now,
28 civilians have been killed and over 100 others injured during
U.S.-British missile and bomb attacks in several incidents.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, two Iraqi civilians were killed and several
others were injured when U.S. warplanes attacked civilian targets
in northern Iraq's Neineva province, INA reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim
of protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims
in the south from "Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain air-raided Iraq in mid-December to
retaliate what they claimed Iraq's non-cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors in charge of eliminating Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
After that attacks, Iraq announced that it does not not
recognize the no-fly zones and would fire at U.S. and British
jets patrolling the zones. Clashes between Iraqi air defense
units and U.S.-British warplanes have almost become daily
occurrence.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz has said that Iraq would
go on confronting U.S.-British warplanes violating Iraqi airspace
regardless of the sacrifices and consequences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
