<HEADLINE> Iran Warns Azerbaijan not to Invite U.S. to Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Former Iranian President
Hashemi Rafsanjani here on Friday warned the Republic of
Azerbaijan not allow the U.S. and NATO to set up military bases on
its soil.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Friday prayers congregation on the campus of
Tehran University, Rafsanjani criticized the recent proposal of
some Azeri officials for presence of U.S. and NATO forces in
Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
The move is a "tremendous portend danger" against the region,
he said, stressing that "the Caspian Sea is a peaceful region and
one of our biggest economic centers," the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"It is very strange to observe why Azerbaijan wants to commit
such an ugly act of paving the way for the presence of the U.S and
NATO in the Caspian and Caucasian region, which will ultimately
cost not only Azerbaijan but whole of the region to pay a high
price for such an adventure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, current chairman of the powerful advisory State
Expediency Council, warned Azerbaijan to think of "the deleterious
effects in the future and its remorse" for paving the way for the
presence of the U.S. and NATO in the region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Azeri officials would take heed of
the crucial issue and not permit the region to be contaminated
and be embroiled in unpredictable events.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, several Azeri officials stated that Azerbaijan
should allow the U.S. or NATO to set up military bases in their
country in order to challenge the threat from Russia and other
regional countries.
</P>
<P>
Senior Iranian officials have stated that Iran would not remain
indifferent if Azerbaijan allows the presence of U.S. and NATO
forces in the former Soviet Republic. 
</P>
</TEXT>
