<HEADLINE> Ethnic Officials Play Big Role In Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region had trained 51,000 ethnic officials by the end
of 1998, accounting for 75 percent of the total officials in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
To date, the amount of ethnic officials makes up 78 percent of
the total officials in the regional government, 67 percent in
prefectural government and 62 percent at magisterial level.
</P>
<P>
Since he became secretary of the magisterial committee of the
Communist Party of China, Puncog, an official who was born and
brought up in Tibet, has succeeded in transforming the formerly
poor Gyangze County and pushed forward its comprehensive
development.
</P>
<P>
There are now numerous ethnic officials like Puncog in Tibet
all playing important roles in regional economic development, said
a local government official.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic officials were trained either in Tibet or other
parts of China. The region has built 10 institutes of higher
learning, eight schools for administration and management skills
and 10 party schools, which train 10,000 ethnic cadres annually.
Meanwhile, some 1,000 Tibetans are sent to provincial universities
each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
