<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo, Pak MPs Deliberate on Treaties to Reduce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The parliamentarians from
Pakistan and India Friday started deliberations on three draft
treaties to reduce the risk of nuclear war nine months after their
governments conducted nuclear tests in May last year.
</P>
<P>
About 100 elected representatives from the two neighbors
attended the first ever Indo-Pak parliamentary conference here
which was titled "Towards Detente in the subcontinent".
</P>
<P>
The three draft treaties taken up by the conference included
agreements on risk-reducing measures of outbreak of a nuclear war,
advanced warnings on ballistic missile tests and prevention of a
nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
The conference will consider the draft treaties which if they
agreed to, the parliamentarians will call upon the respective
governments to sign.
</P>
<P>
The first draft treaty requires both parties "to maintain and
to improve their existing organizational and technical
arrangements to guard against the accidental or unauthorized use
of nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
It also calls on the two sides to instantly exchange
information about any accidental test.
</P>
<P>
The second draft treaty binds both countries to "act in such a
manner as to prevent the development of situations capable of
causing a dangerous exacerbation of their relations, as to avoid a
military confrontation, and as to exclude the outbreak of a
nuclear war between them."
</P>
<P>
The third draft treaty calls for instant negotiations in case
of an imminent threat of nuclear war between the two.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five parliamentary members from India's major parties
including the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) and the main
opposition Congress Party Friday sat face to face with their
Pakistani counterparts in the first ever non-official dialogue
among them on major issues that confront the two south Asian
nations.
</P>
<P>
Twenty members from the ruling Pakistan Muslim League (PML)
attended the meeting, while the main opposition Pakistan People's
Party (PPP) led by former prime minister Benazir Mhutto also took
part in the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
