<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Smaller Firms Expected to Boost Economic Growth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- As China's market-economy reform
moves deeper, small and medium-sized enterprises are becoming a
major growth factor amid an overall tight economic environment at
home and abroad, according to some observers.
</P>
<P>
The development of the Chinese economy, of course, needs the
participation of large enterprises. But the small and medium
firms, with their relatively flexible operations, are an important
force for boosting supply and demand, and thereby stimulating
economic growth. This is needed at a time of worldwide economic
uncertainty, said Wu Jinglian, a noted economist with the
Development and Research Center of the State Council, China's
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
After decades of a planned economy, the majority of China's
large state-owned enterprises have been plagued by overstaffing,
poor management, and low efficiency. In the economic
transformation that began in the late 1970s, the small and medium
firms have generally performed better than the larger ones in
becoming more market-driven and efficiency-oriented.
</P>
<P>
The Zhonglian Environmental Protection Equipment Co. Ltd. in
east China's Anhui Province was formed on the basis of Anhui No. 1
Textile Machinery, which went bankrupt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to its flexible operations in developing the most
advanced type of sewage treatment systems in China, this company
was able to turn in 1.62 million yuan in taxes last year, more
than triple the amount for 1997.
</P>
<P>
"As a small business, we don't have any capital advantage, and
have had to play entirely by market principles," said company
chairman Hu Ziwei.
</P>
<P>
In Anhui, the cradle of China's rural reforms, there are an
increasing number of small and medium-sized firms which have
succeeded on the basis of flexible operations and improved
management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Surveillance Improved in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- More food samples were taken
for microbiological and chemical testings in Hong Kong in the
first 11 months of 1998, the Department of Health announced here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Director of Health Dr. Gloria Tam pointed out that
some 50,000 samples were taken for microbiological testings during
the period as compared with 48,000 food samples taken for testing
for the corresponding period in 1997 and 43,000 samples in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The increase was due to more testings done for poultry and
shellfish in 1998.
</P>
<P>
This was in response to outbreaks of avian flu and cholera
respectively.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the number of samples taken for testing is
equivalent to a sampling ratio of eight per 1,000 people annually
and compares favorably with the internationally accepted standard
of three per 1,000 people every year.
</P>
<P>
The microbiological testings results indicated that there were
significant improvements in two categories of foods, namely fish
and shellfish, she said.
</P>
<P>
As for chemical testings, 32,000 food samples had been taken
for chemical testings in 1998. This was a substantial increase
over the 31,000 samples tested in 1997 and 27,000 samples tested
in 1996. The increase was mainly due to more testings done for
pesticides and beta-agonists in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The percentage of unsatisfactory samples tested for chemicals
were 1.56 in 1998, 1.38 in 1997 and 1.7 in 1996. The 1998's figure
would have shown more improvements had it not been for the finding
of ciguatera in coral reef fish and beta-agonists in pork and pig'
s internal organs.
</P>
<P>
Together, the two sets of microbiological and chemical testing
figures indicated that the overall food hygiene standard in Hong
Kong was improving, Tam said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
