<HEADLINE> Japan to Inject Public Funds Into 15 Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Financial Reconstruction
Commission (FRC) decided Friday to inject 7.45 trillion yen (64.8
billion U.S. dollars) in public funds into 15 major banks in a bid
to relieve the banking crisis that is hampering the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
The commission, a government body charged with reviving the
banking sector, has been negotiating with the banks over the
disposal of their bad debts and replenishment of their capital
bases, to restore confidence in the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The commission made the decision and relayed it to each of the
banks after a preliminary screening of the banks' plans to write
off bad loans and restructure their operations.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the commission show that Japan's
financial institutions had more than 73 trillion yen (634.8
billion dollars) in bad loans as of September 1998, accounting for
12.2 percent to the total credit volume.
</P>
<P>
According to the commission, individual banks will receive
varying sums depending on their financial situation.
</P>
<P>
The government will pay the funds by purchasing preferred
stocks in the banks.
</P>
<P>
The banks include Sumitomo Bank, Sanwa Bank, Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank, Fuji Bank and Sakura Bank.
</P>
<P>
Japan's largest commercial bank, the Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
declined to accept the government offer of financial aid, saying
it can raise funds from private companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
