<HEADLINE> Nigeria's PDP Party to Pick Presidential Candidate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former head of state Olusegun Obasanjo and former
vice-president Alex Ekwueme are among the seven presidential
aspirants of the party, PDP's National Publicity Secretary,
Senator Anietie Okon said Thursday in capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
The seven aspirants will contest the presidential ticket of the
party at the PDP special national convention scheduled to be held
on Saturday and Sunday in Jos, Plateau State, local media Friday
quoted Okon as saying.
</P>
<P>
Okon said that 2,500 delegates will participate in the
convention for nominating the presidential flagbearer of the party
for the February 27 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
General Obasanjo enunciated a six-point agenda for national
reconstruction when he addressed Zamfara State delegates to the
national convention on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agenda, Obasanjo will give priority to food and
agriculture, education, investment and employment in his national
reconstruction agenda
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said that one of the motivating factors for his quest
for political leadership is the challenge to facilitate the
reunification of Nigeria and the reconstruction of decadent
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
If elected, he said, he will facilitate the urgent return of
the country to the league of progressive nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that Nigeria who was in 1979 during his tenure as
head of state in the league of the first 50 most prosperous
nations in terms of economic stability, has now plummeted to
become one of the 20 poorest nations in the world.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo said that there was a lot of reformation and
reconstruction to do in the country, maintaining that he is "the
bridge between the North and South of Nigeria, the East and North,
Christians and Muslims, military and civilians and between the
international community and Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another PDP presidential aspirant Ekwueme told a
press conference Thursday in Abuja that he believed in the unity
of Nigeria as an indivisible entity, stressing the entire
Federation of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He denied ever advocating confederation or regional army,
saying "There is absolutely no record of where I have ever
advocated confederation for this country; nor that each zone must
have its own separate army."
</P>
<P>
Ekwueme said that in keeping with the vision of the founding
fathers of Nigeria who adopted the federal system in order to
preserve the unity in diversity, he has always been an apostle of
federalism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
