<HEADLINE> Kenya Takes Measures to Ensure Air Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
begun the rehabilitation of the airports and the replacement of
aging air traffic control equipment to ensure air safety and
security in the country.
</P>
<P>
Transport and Communications Minister William Ole Ntimama said
Thursday that the government will improve air navigation
infrastructure in a bid to make the country's airports compliant
with standards of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In pursuit of aviation safety and low cost of flight operation,
the government will exploit computer-based technology and space
satellites which allow flexible air route structures, the Kenya
Times newspaper Friday quoted Ntimama as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that to guarantee speedy and efficient replacement of
obsolete air control facilities, the government has established an
air traffic management system coordination committee to supervise
the entire airport rehabilitation exercise across the country.
</P>
<P>
Another move will be taken in June to de-link the Directorate
of Civil Aviation (DCA), a regulating body, from the mainstream
civil service.
</P>
<P>
The de-linking will lead to the separation of policy regulators
and formulators from air service providers, such as airliners and
airports, therefore making the DCA more efficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
