<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Gene May Help Some People Avoid Heart Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists said
Thursday they had found more evidence that a gene that helps
control blood fat levels may let some people escape heart disease
even if they are overweight or have high cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
Kardia and colleagues at the University of Michigan said they
examined 329 men and women, who were under the age of 60 had no
sign of heart disease or stroke.
</P>
<P>
CT scans were used to see how clogged their arteries were, and
then the volunteers's genes were examined, said the scientists who
found a gene called ApoE affects blood cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
Scientists said there are three different known versions of
ApoE --ApoE-2, ApoE-3, and ApoE-4 -- and everyone gets two copies
of each gene, so 6 different combinations are possible. Most
people have two ApoE-3 genes, they added.
</P>
<P>
Kardia's team found women who had one ApoE-3 and one ApoE-4
gene had plaque in their arteries if they tended to be overweight
and also had high levels of triglycerides, which are one type of
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
In men who had one ApoE-3 and one ApoE-4 gene, the risk rose if
they were overweight, but if they just had high cholesterol they
did not have a higher risk, the scientists reported.
</P>
<P>
"These kinds of studies might help explain some of the
variation and have implications for treatment," said Kardia in the
statement issued by the American Heart Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
