<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK, US Propose UN to Monitor Libyans in Jail for Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is the latest effort made by Britain and U.S. to break the
stalemate over the Lockerbie airliner bombing and to persuade
Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi to hand over the suspects for trial
in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
In December,1988, a Pan Am flight was bombed over the Scotland
town of Lockerbie, killing all 270 people on board.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British investigators accused two Libyan agents of
planting the bomb and have been trying to bring the suspects to
face trial in the Netherlands. They also insisted that the two
should serve their sentences in Scotland if convicted their crimes.
</P>
<P>
Libya has declined to let the two suspects face trial, saying
it does not want them to serve their prison sentence in Scotland
if convicted.
</P>
<P>
"In order to counter Libyan claims that these people would be
denied their human rights, we've said we would be happy for U.N.
monitors to attend the jail and ensure they weren't maltreated in
any way," a British Foreign Office spokesman said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
He said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan had approved the
proposal and passed it on to Libya in the last two weeks, and was
waiting for a reply.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. monitors would make sure the suspects would not be
interrogated by British or American police or security services as
Libya is concerned, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners' dietary, religious and cultural needs would also
be respected, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Britain had proposed that Libya could open a special
consulate in Scotland to have an official presence nearby to
monitor the conditions of the jailed Libyans if they would serve
their sentences there.
</P>
<P>
South African envoy Jakes Gerwel visited Gaddafi this week in a
fresh bid to end the Lockerbie impasse. Britain welcomed in last
week the visit but insisted at the same time that Gerwel would not
negotiate with Libya on behalf of Britain.  
</P>
</TEXT>
