<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phnom Penh's Gun-control Campaign Successful: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The campaign to crack down
on illegal weapons in Phnom Penh, capital of Cambodia, was
successful, according to Phnom Penh's first deputy governor Chea
Sophara.
</P>
<P>
Beginning November 1, 1998, local officials and police went
door to door to ask residents if they had any illegal weapons and
explosives. Except those who have gun licenses, all illegal
weapons must be confiscated or handed over to the municipality
through its "buy-back" scheme.
</P>
<P>
The municipality has been paying 40,000 riel (about 10 U.S.
dollars) for AK-47s, 50,000 riel (about 13 dollars) for shotguns
and 5,000 riel (just over one dollar) for grenades.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures show that of the more than 15,000 households
inspected as of February 2, 9,922 had guns. But only 12 percent of
them were illegal.
</P>
<P>
According to a city official, the municipality so far has
collected 665 guns and at least 70 grenades.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sophara was quoted Friday by the Cambodian Daily as saying
that "We've been receiving illegal weapons every week. I think our
gun-control campaign is successful."
</P>
<P>
The campaign is aimed at reducing the number of illegal weapons
and explosives and ultimately helping to reduce armed crimes in
the capital, Chea Sophara said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
