<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Remains Biggest Refugee Group 10 Years After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 12 (Xinhua) -- With more than 2.6 million
Afghans in exile, Afghanistan remains the single largest refugee
country in the world a decade after the last Soviet soldier left
the Afghan soil, the U.N. refugee agency, UNHCR, said Friday in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement marked the 10th anniversary of the Soviet
withdrawal from Afghanistan falling on February 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Since the first batch of Afghans fled the Soviet invasion 20
years ago, Afghanistan has owned the biggest group of refugees in
the world for the consecutive 19 years, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1979 there were already 400,000 Afghan refugees
in Pakistan and other 200,000 in Iran. By February 15, 1989, the
date when the last Soviet soldier stepped out of Afghanistan, the
refugee number had risen to a staggering 6.2 million.
</P>
<P>
Since the Soviet withdrawal, more than 4 million refugees,
almost two thirds of the total, have returned to their country,
according to the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
