<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Economic Growth Up in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot economic growth rate
in 1998 rose by 5 percent, compare with 2.5 percent in 1997, the
Cyprus Weekly reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The latest report issued by Cyprus' Statistics Department said
that the Cyprus economy continued its revival in 1998, fostered
mainly by the boom of tourism.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in Cyprus reached 2.1 million in 1998, an
increase of 6.8 percent from 1997, which earned the country 843
million Cyprus pounds (1,686 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
As a result of the pickup of economic activity, demand for
labor showed a recovery. At the end of October 1998, the
unemployment rate dropped to 3.2 percent of the economically
active population.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, as measured by the consumer price index,
also fell to 2.2 percent in 1998, compared to 3.6 percent in 1997,
thanks to a much lower growth in the prices of local products and
electricity, and a minor increase in rents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Doctors Discover New Hereditary Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus Institute of
Neurology and Genetics (CING) has discovered a new hereditary
neurological disorder in Jordan, which can cause paralysis of
legs, the Cyprus Weekly reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The new disease was named "Jerash Hereditary Motor Neuropathy"
after the mountainous region in Jordan, where it is prevalent in a
number of isolated villages, Lefcos Middleton, director of the
CING said Thursday at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Middleton said the research, carried out in collaboration with
the University Hospital and the King Hussein Hospital in Amman,
found 40 percent of the screened 120 people last year in three
Jerash villages suffering the disease.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the disorder causes lower limb paralysis to
children of 3-5 years old and the paralysis spreads upwards as
they grow older.
</P>
<P>
The disorder is prevalent in small mid-eastern communities in
Jordan, where close relatives, including first cousins, tend to
marry, he said.
</P>
<P>
CING geneticist Roulla Christodoulou confirmed the gene for
this disease was mapped on chromosome 9.
</P>
<P>
He said when both parents are carriers of the gene, there is a
25 percent chance for their offspring to develop the disease, a 25
percent chance of normality and a 50 percent chance become a
carrier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
