<HEADLINE> Turkey, Croatia Willing to Boost Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Croatia have
expressed that there are a large number of opportunities for
boosting bilateral cooperation, particularly in economy, defense
industry and investment.
</P>
<P>
Five agreements in cooperation in justice, science, technology,
customs services, agriculture and veterinary services have been
signed during the visit here by Croatian President Franjo Tudjman,
who left Turkey Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
During his three-day visit, Tudjman and his Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel also exchanged views on a number of regional and
international issues, voicing concerns over the turbulent
situation in Kosovo and hoping the 1995 Dayton Peace Accord, which
ended the war in Bosnia, will be fully implemented.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia, have heightened
since last February when bloody clashes erupted between Serbian
police and ethnic Albanians, who, comprising 90 percent of the
Kosovo population, demand independence from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
At a gathering of the Turkish - Croatian Business Council in
Ankara, Demirel has stressed that the present bilateral trade did
not reflect the genuine potential of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, trade volume between the two countries reached about
35 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Demirel pointed out that "our target in bilateral trade is 100
million dollars in the short term and 500 million dollars in the
long term."
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Turkey wishes to take an active part in
infrastructure projects in Croatia and Turkish contractors are
particularly interested in the construction of highways in
Croatia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
