<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Marginally Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
finished marginally up Friday, after failing to sustain an
overnight rally above the 65 U.S. cent mark as commodity prices
sank to historic lows.
</P>
<P>
European buying Thursday night propelled the Australian unit to
65.08 U.S. cents but a 21-year low in a leading commodities index
saw the domestic currency sold off gradually throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
At the close of trading the domestic unit was at 64.63 U.S.
cents from 64.53 Thursday, after spending the day between 64.52
and 64.78.
</P>
<P>
MMS Standard &AMP; Poor's said the Commodity Research Bureau Index
fell to a new 21-year low Thursday night, closing down 1.21 at
187.16 after hitting a low of 186.99.
</P>
<P>
"That probably hasn't helped the Aussie's prospects," Colonial
State Bank treasury manager Nick Volanakis said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Japanese currency also weakened briefly during the
day before recovering the ground, which could have impacted
negatively on the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Japanese interest was focused on a meeting of the Bank of Japan
and speculation of an easing in monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
At the trading close, the local currency was buying 0.5753 euro
from 0.5700 and it was trading at 73.74 from 73.65 against
Japanese yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
