<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Higher With Banks Performing Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares ended
trading firmer with banking and telco stocks among the better
performers while BHP weighed on the resources sector.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index accelerated 22.5 points by the close
to 2889.5, after briefly touching 2903.5.
</P>
<P>
All industrials index firmed 48.3 points to 5226.9 but all
resources moved 0.9 of a point lower to 968.8 points.
</P>
<P>
Dicksons broker Jon Hancock said the positive performance in
the majors was driven by the two percent rise on the Dow Jones
Thursday night and strong news-driven rises in selected stocks.
</P>
<P>
National turnover figures showed 401.3 million shares traded
worth 1.343 billion Australian dollars (859.5 million U.S.
dollars) with 705 rising shares, 553 falling shares and 413 were
steady.
</P>
<P>
The banks accounted for much of the rise in the all ordinaries
with the banking sub index climbing almost two percent to 6639.6.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank was up 65.9 cents. ANZ and Commonwealth
Bank of Australia closed up 23 cents respectively.
</P>
<P>
Telstra Corp was up 25 cents on a turnover of 8.9 million
shares. Rival Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus was down four cents, while it
topped market turnover on a volume of 20.8 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The resources sector was led lower by BHP, which slipped 21
cents, while the other resources leaders improved.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto jumped 35 cents, North grew two and WMC added three
cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 12.2 points, or 1.16 percent, higher at
1064.2.
</P>
<P>
The price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 286.85 U.S.
dollars per ounce compared to Thursday's close 287.10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
