<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Orders Drug Test for Police, Guards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Friday ordered drug tests for police, security guards, owners of
security agencies and gun owners before they can be issued with
necessary licenses and permits.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum to the Philippine National Police (PNP),
Interior and Local Governments Undersecretary Ronaldo V. PunoPuno
said the drug testing is part of the efforts to address the drug
abuse problem.
</P>
<P>
The order was an apparent attempt to abate crime incidents
involving drug-using policemen, security guards and civilian gun
owners, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum provides mandatory drug testing as a
pre-condition for passing the annual physical and medical
examinations of PNP members.
</P>
<P>
The testing is also required for people who apply for operating
or managing a security agency, being employed as a security guard,
and owning any firearms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coke, Pepsi Tie in Corporate Volume Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Coca-Cola Company and
Pepsi-Cola Co. led U.S. soft drink industry's growth last year,
with each company selling 4.5 percent more soda pop in 1998 than
they did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to separate reports published Thursday by the trade
publication Beverage Digest and the research concern Beverage
Marketing Corp., Coke also gained 0.6 market share points and
continues to top the industry with a 44.5 corporate market share
while Pepsi's overall corporate market share increased 0.5 points
to 31.4, continuing to stand as No. 2 in the soft drink industry.
</P>
<P>
Beverage Digest said overall industry sales rose 3.0 percent
while Beverage Marketing pegged the growth at 3.4 percent. Of the
top 10 companies, only Coke and Pepsi gained market share in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The total retail value of the U.S. carbonated soft drink
industry in 1998 was 56.3 billion U.S. dollars, up from 54.7
billion dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
