<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Calls for Fight Against Graft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIR0BI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Simon
Nyachae has asked all Kenyans to join in the fight against
corruption so as to improve governance and hasten economic growth
of the country.
</P>
<P>
"The government alone cannot eradicate corrupting, not even the
recently strengthened Anti-Corruption Authority can do it unless
the whole society participates," Nyachae said here Thursday at the
opening of the 7th annual economic symposium of the Institute of
Certified Public Accountants.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to eradicate corruption must be carried out at all
levels, the East African Standard newspaper Friday quoted Nyachae
as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The minister cautioned the country's accountants and auditors
against colluding with some road contractors to fleece the
government of millions of Shillings.
</P>
<P>
The minister decried the poor state of the country's roads,
telecommunications, water and port facilities.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government was spending heavily on road
repairs yet contractors only did shoddy jobs while accountants and
auditors were failing Kenyans by not telling how their hard earned
money was being spent.
</P>
<P>
He said that the government is taking measures to improve
efficiency in utilization of the funds allocated to
infrastructures. The general public must assume the role of
watchdog and insist on quality, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
