<HEADLINE> China to Encourage Strong Companies to Invest Abroad (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China will encourage companies
with strong technical expertise and experience background to
invest overseas in order to increase exports, according to the
Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Speaking during an exclusive Friday interview with Xinhua News
Agency, MOFTEC officials said China will introduce special
policies to encourage companies in the machinery and electronics,
light industry and textile sectors to invest abroad.
</P>
<P>
Such companies will be encouraged to establish overseas
ventures to assemble and manufacture products such as automobiles,
motorcycles, small farm machinery and equipment, television sets,
refrigerators, washing machines and electric fans.
</P>
<P>
The policies will be in line with MOFTEC's export targets
announced earlier this month by Minister Shi Guangsheng. Shi said
MOFTEC will strengthen efforts to promote overseas processing with
domestically manufactured materials in order increase exports of
Chinese products, equipment, raw materials, parts and labor
services.
</P>
<P>
The minister described the policies as a major step of
restructuring the national economy and boosting China's exports in
1999. He added that the policies will be carried out on the basis
of sufficient feasibility studies and careful selection, with
priority placed on economic returns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Encourage Strong Companies to Invest Abroad (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOFTEC officials noted that participating companies will be
highly competitive, and will feature strong management expertise,
advanced operating mechanisms, experience with overseas businesses
and exports, as well as high creditability.
</P>
<P>
China will select 120 large enterprises and 1,000 key
enterprises to undertake pilot investments abroad in the form of
equipment, expertise, raw materials and parts.
</P>
<P>
Chinese companies had established over 5,600 projects in more
than 160 countries and regions, including Asia, Africa, Latin
America, Eastern Europe and Central Asia, by the end of 1998.
Related projects involved total investments of over nine billion
US dollars, with contracted investments from Chinese partners
amounting to 6.33 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The wide-ranging projects cover resources development,
processing and assembly, transportation, engineering construction,
pharmaceuticals, tourism and consulting services, in addition to
other areas common to the trade sector.
</P>
<P>
Sun Weiyan, president of the University of the International
Business and Economics, said overseas investments will benefit
both China and recipient areas.
</P>
<P>
"Investments will help increase exports of Chinese equipment,
technology, raw materials, semi-finished products and parts, in
addition to raising employment rates in areas attracting
investment, helping to restructure local economies, upgrading
technological levels and multiplying market supply," said Sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
