<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reports Rising Tax Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China's January tax revenues
reached 81.84 billion yuan, up 26.6 percent from the same month n
1998.
</P>
<P>
The figure accounted for 8.7 percent of the projected 1999 tax
revenues, according to a report released today by the State
Administration of Taxation.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the upward momentum to the stable
domestic economic performance and expanded revenue sources, as
well as the consistent efforts of taxation departments nationwide
to tighten controls over tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Most tax items, including value-added, consumption, enterprise
and personal income taxes, grew by an average 30 percent, with
various items approaching 100 percent growth, according to the
report. It also pointed out that tax revenues for major industries,
including tobacco petroleum, liquor, textile and coal sectors,
grew by over 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
China collected industrial and commercial tax revenues totaling
855.2 billion yuan in 1998, with this year's target set at 946
billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
