<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Reject Probe Into Military Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan Parliament has
rejected a motion seeking to set up a select committee to probe
abuse of power and corruption in military procurement.
</P>
<P>
The motion, tabled by Aggrey Awori who is known for sounding a
different note in the legislature, attracted enormous opposition
Thursday, the New Vision daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A number of MPs said that the suggested probe will expose the
country's military might or weakness.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan State Minister of Defense, Steven Kavuma said Thursday
that the select committee is not necessary because the
parliamentary committee handling defense affairs intends to
investigate this matter.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the motion, which seeks a thorough probe into
the purchase of helicopter,gun ships, tanks, radar and missiles,
could throw the country into a catastrophe if not stopped.
</P>
<P>
However, Awori said a report shows that some officers received
a commission on the purchase of the helicopters and the
parliament, as a watchdog of the government, should not be tired
of setting up another select committee.
</P>
<P>
It is entitled to know how public funds have been spent and
national security maintained, he added.
</P>
<P>
Some MPs have accused the army of paying inflated prices for
defective helicopters and tanks, saying that the officers
responsible for that purchase got huge sums of commission in the
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
