<HEADLINE> World Champion Xiong Ni To Stage Comeback at World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Olympic champion Xiong Ni will
come out of his retirement since 1997, choosing three World Cup
diving grand prixs in May to test his strength before the 2000
Sydney Olympics, an official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Jihong, chief of the national diving team, said that the
three-time Olympian has resumed his training in February and will
attend the three FINA-sponsored events held in Canada, the United
States and Mexico which traditionally featured a strong field.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Ni, 25, had put his retirment on his agenda after his
dream of Olympic champion finally came true in the 1996 Games,
becoming the first Chinese to win a men's springboard gold medal
at the Games.
</P>
<P>
The official announcement came when he collected the title of
three-meter springboard in the Eighth National Games in October
1997.
</P>
<P>
Since his departure, the traditional diving powerhouse has been
hit by a series of setbacks on international arena, chiefly
bowing to the challenge from the arch-rival Dimitry Sautin of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the slump of international performance
partly to the premature retirement of some well-known athletes
like Xiong Ni.
</P>
<P>
Amid the calling for his comeback, the world champion resumed
training in May, 1998, vowing to produce impressive performance in
the Sydney Games if he gets selected.
</P>
<P>
But his aspiration was dumped by the failure to represent China
in the New Zealand World Cup Grand Prix in January, which cast
shadow over his possibility of presence in the turn-of-the-century
Games.
</P>
<P>
As concern arised that he might say goodbye to diving forever,
the world champion returned to the diving pool again after he had
been persuaded by the Chinese Swimming Sports Association (CSSA).
</P>
<P>
CSSA has hoped to beef up its strength in next year's Sydney
Olympics against a Russian line-up spearheaded by the seemingly
invincible great Dimitry Sautin, double titlist at the world
championships last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
