<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera kills 28 people in Kenya's Coast Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Provincial Medical Director S.K. Shariff said that the cause of
the outbreak of the disease is believed to be contaminated water
from the River Jombo.
</P>
<P>
More than 160 people have been admitted with cholera to the
four health centres in the area, which has an estimated population
of 90,000. Schools in the area have been closed and classrooms
are being used for wards for hundreds of patients receiving
oral-rehydration treatment.
</P>
<P>
Local councillors earlier reported the dealth toll reaching
132, but Shariff denied this figure, saying he could not account
for the people who died in remote villages.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Daily Nation Friday quoted Shariff as saying that
three mobile clinics have been set up to help fight the epidemic.
A huge consignment of antibiotics and intravenous fluids has been
sent to the area.
</P>
<P>
To curb the spread of the disease, four medical teams of three
people each have pitched tents in villages of the area to educate
people about basic hygiene, environmental cleanliness and
sanitation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
