<HEADLINE> U.S., Israel Working to Link Arrow 2 to U.S. Radars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Israel
are seeking ways to share real-time information on missile defense
and to link the Arrow 2 anti-ballistic missile to U.S. radar
systems, a local daily said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are working to ensure that they can exchange
missile command and control information, a U.S. general, who was
here on a routine inspection of the Arrow 2 project, told the
Jerusalem Post Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brig. General Daniel L. Montgomery, the program executive
officer for the U.S. Missile Defense Systems, said Israel and
the U.S. envision cooperation between Israel's Arrow 2 defense
systems and U.S. units in the region, which makes the exchange
of information very important.
</P>
<P>
He said the two countries are also working closely to link
Arrow 2 with Patriot anti-ballistic missile systems, so that any
batteries deployed in the region would be able to share data.
</P>
<P>
Israel last year successfully conducted the first comprehensive
test launch of the Arrow 2 system, which is designed to shoot down
incoming missiles at speeds up to two miles per second traveling
10 or 25 miles above the earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
The Arrow, which costs 1.6 billion U.S. dollars and mostly
funded by the U.S., is expected to be fully operational in less
than a year after undergoing further testing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
