<HEADLINE> Netherlands to Grant Angola $7M in Humanitarian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Netherlands has decided to
donate seven million U.S. Dollars in humanitarian aid to help the
Angolan people affected by escalating conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Dutch ambassador to Luanda, Jan Heric Berg said in Kuito,
capital of Bie Province, Thursday that the funds will be used in
humanitarian programs implemented by the United Nations
institutions, charity groups and non- governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Journal de Angola newspaper Friday quoted the ambassador
as saying that the Dutch government will give priority to the
programs of the International Committee of the Red Cross,
including rescuing the civilians wounded in the conflicts between
the Angolan government troops and the rebel UNITA forces.
</P>
<P>
Emergency aid for the war-created refugees is also among the
priorities of the humanitarian programs.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch ambassador said that in order to relieve the
suffering of the Angolan people, the Netherlands has offered
humanitarian assistance worth five million Dollars in the past
three years.
</P>
<P>
There are some 40,000 refugees in central Kuito city where Berg
was paying a visit. The battles between the government troops and
the forces of Jonas Savimbi's National Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) around the city had been the most
fiercing ones since civil war broke out once again in the southern
African country last December. 
</P>
