<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Arrest Ex-Rwandan Minister in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan police have arrested a
former Rwandan minister indicted by a United Nations tribunal for
his alleged role in the 1994 genocide of an estimated 500,000
people, a tribunal spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper Friday quoted the
spokesman, Kingsley Moghalu, as saying that former Rwandan
information minister Eliezer Niyitegeka was arrested at his home
in suburban Nairobi on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
He was tracked down by prosecutors of the U.N. International
Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) based in the northern
Tanzanian town of Arusha, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The prosecutors accuse Niyitegeka of leading massacres against
ethnic Tutsi hiding in the hills of western Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR spokesman said that "the Kenyan police at our request
arrested Niyitegeka. We are in the process of transferring him to
Arusha."
</P>
<P>
The ICTR was set up to bring the genocide's main architects to
justice. So far, its court has convicted three men, sentencing
two to its maximum penalty of life imprisonment and a third to 15
years in jail.
</P>
<P>
Niyitegeka was the 11th genocide suspect to have been arrested
in Kenya, where many prominent Hutus fled after the massacres.
</P>
</TEXT>
