<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS-Fireworks Ban Lifted Northern Chinese City Lifts Ban on Fireworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shijiazhuang, capital of north
China's Hebei Province, will lift the five-year ban on fireworks
during the Spring Festival, the Chinese Lunar New Year, which
falls on February 16 this year, the "China Youth News" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
However, the time and places for the fireworks displays will be
limited. People will not be allowed to set off firecrackers at
hospitals, train and bus stations, museums, libraries, markets,
busy shopping streets, government institutions, gas stations, and
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
Only small and low-altitude fireworks are allowed to be sold,
and the municipal supply and marketing cooperatives have been
designated as the sole sellers. Individuals and privately owned
shops, which used to produce low-quality firecrackers, are
prohibited from selling these products.
</P>
<P>
Fireworks were banned in Shijiazhuang on December 1, 1994 after
the city's People's Congress approved a regulation prohibiting
fireworks in urban districts. The ban was lifted after a survey
among the local people.
</P>
<P>
Ten other cities in Hebei are divided on whether or not to lift
the ban. Those favoring the ban say it will help keep the
environment clean, reduce noise, and prevent fires and injuries.
Those against the ban say fireworks displays help create a festive
atmosphere.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 07:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese President Visits Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Emile
Lahoud left here on Friday for Damascus on a one-day
official visit to Syria, his first tour abroad since he took
office last November.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of People radio quoted presidential palace sources
as saying the president will hold talks with his Syrian
counterpart Hafez Assad and other senior officials on bilateral
ties and peace process in the region.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will also focus on the situation in south
Lebanon where Israeli occupation forces and Lebanese guerrillas
exchange fire almost everyday.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north
from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting
to oust Israelis and its allies the South Lebanon Army out of
the country.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two countries' leaders will reaffirm
the entwinement of Lebanese and Syrian tracks in the peace
talks with Israel, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying Syrian Golan Heights it captured in the
1967 Middle East War. Its negotiations to return the strategic
plateau with Syria was suspended in 1996 when Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to power.
</P>
<P>
In April last year, the Jewish state offered to withdraw
from south Lebanon provided security arrangements are reached
with the Beirut government beforehand.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria, which has 35,000 troops in
Lebanon, rejected the offer, asking Israel to leave the
country without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Israel accused Syria of holding south Lebanon as a
bargaining chip to seek a full Israeli withdrawal which will
also include Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud, former army commander, was elected as Lebanon's 11th
president after allegedly enjoying both the approval of Assad
and Lebanese popular support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
