<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academy of Sciences "Reinvents" Institutes as Part of Well-Funded Reform (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide project aimed at
restructuring research institutes, universities and enterprises
has been launched with the approval of a Ministry of Finance grant
of 5.4 billion yuan over the next three years to the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The reorganization of the academy by the State Council, known
as the CAS Knowledge Innovation Program, will act as a pilot which,
if successful, will later be extended across the country.
</P>
<P>
The large amount of money is unprecedented and is on top of
annual administrative fees, or head count fees, that the CAS will
continue to receive, and will be distributed over a three year
period.
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand, we need the money badly to carry out in-depth
structural reform; on the other hand, there is also a great amount
of pressure on us because we cannot use a lack of money as an
excuse if we fail to come up with tangible results," says CAS vice
president Yan Yixun, who describes the CAS innovation program as "
an unprecedented opportunity as well as a great challenge" for the
academy.
</P>
<P>
While 600 million of the 5.4 billion is being earmarked for
supporting those coming to work at CAS from abroad, most will be
used to cover the costs of the more radical reform measures needed
within CAS. It plans to reduce its research institutes by one
third in number and retain only 30,000 fixed positions out of the
current 68,000 by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Those given fixed-contracts, which involves better working
conditions, will enjoy more research funds, but some 30,000 of the
current army of CAS employees will lose their once-permanent
positions and will have to look for temporary appointments either
inside or outside CAS, or re-train.
</P>
<P>
Making arrangements for those laid-off will take up part of the
funding, according to CAS spokesman Li Yunling.
</P>
<P>
She says the aim of the CAS Knowledge Innovation Program is to
establish a modern scientific research system within the academy
that is in accordance with international practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 07:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The United States and Israel are working out ways to share
real-time information on missile defense and link the Arrow 2
anti-ballistic missile to U.S. radar systems, a U.S. general said
Thursday. He said the two countries are also working closely to
link Arrow 2 with Patriot anti-ballistic missile systems, so that
any batteries deployed in the region would be able to share data.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- The security establishment has received very serious
warnings about the intention of terrorist organizations, especially
Hamas, to kidnap Israeli soldiers to use as bargaining chips.
Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz disclosed Thursday that in the past
month two attempts to kidnap soldiers were foiled.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Efforts are under way to prevent ultra-Orthodox from
staging a planned mass demonstration Sunday against the judicial
system. Dozens of non-Orthodox organizations are also planning
counter-demonstrations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Academy of Sciences "Reinvents" Institutes as Part of Well-Funded Reform (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
With the sole exception of the Dalian Chemical Physics
Institute, most projects are in the initial stage of discussing
details for restructuring plans, or are awaiting the green light
from the CAS to proceed with detailed plan. Despite lingering
difficulties concerning the division of practical reorganization,
many believe that measures will be carried out to alleviate the
welfare burden on the academy's institutes.
</P>
<P>
Companies, totally separate from the institutes, will be set up
to provide services such as transportation, while an office will
be set up to handle Communist Party affairs, issues involving
trade union membership, family planning work, and daily business
other than research.
</P>
<P>
Institutes will proceed in line with national housing and
medical reforms, and will no longer provide apartments or medical
care for employees. However, a measure of assistance will still be
provided in the form of housing subsidies and medical insurance
partially funded with employee contributions.
</P>
<P>
Deng Maicun, the 39-year-old director of the Dalian Chemical
Physics Institute, expressed hope that a decision will be reached
sooner rather than later. He said that permitting the
establishment of a true board will enable the institute to attract
outside investment and build true partnerships with investors.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the CAS is currently the sole investor
in the institute and thus the establishment of a board is out of
the question.
</P>
<P>
Laboratory heads, including the institute director, will be
reelected every four years, and individuals holding fixed
positions will be awarded two-year contracts. Laboratory heads
holding a position for two successive terms will become permanent
CAS researchers.
</P>
<P>
Various application restrictions, including age, are currently
in force. Yi Baolian, a researcher at the institute and member of
the selection committee, said individuals over 56 years of age
will be ineligible for positions as laboratory heads. He noted
that youth prevails, and pointed out that eight of the 10 new
laboratory heads are under 40.
</P>
<P>
The eventual success of the CAS Knowledge Innovation Program,
or lack thereof, will determine if related experiences are
extended to research sections in universities and enterprises.
However, Yi pointed out that it is "still much too early " to tell
whether or not this task can be mastered. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Fall for 4th Consecutive Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian wool prices have
fallen for the fourth consecutive week, dropping by a further 1.5
percent at auctions in Sydney, Melbourne and Fremantle this week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Wool Industries Secretariat (AWIS) said in its
weekly report that markets in the east, north, south and west all
fell by seven cents this week.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator ended at 484 cents (310 U.S.
cents)/kg clean, markets in the north and south ended at 494 and
475 cents (316 and 304 U.S. cents)/kg clean and the western region
indicator ended at 441 cents (282 U.S. cents)/kg clean.
</P>
<P>
A total of 78,016 bales were offered, with 19.8 percent passed
in -- 17.3 percent in Sydney, 18.5 percent in Melbourne and 24.9
percent in Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
"The market is just drifting along at the present time with no
positive direction from customers overseas," AWIS said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
