<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 07:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Army Chief Warns Against Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shaul Mofaz, Chief of
General Staff of Israeli military, has warned that the Islamic
militant group Hamas is stepping up its attempts to kidnap
Israeli soldiers, local daily The Jerusalem Post reported on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Mofaz as saying that Hamas wanted to use
kidnaped Israeli soldiers as a bargaining chip in the
negotiations for the release of Palestinian prisoners in Israeli
jails.
</P>
<P>
Mofaz noted that Hamas activists have tried to kidnap Israeli
soldiers at least twice in the past month and in one case, the
army "paid a price" to foil the attempt.
</P>
<P>
It is assumed that Mofaz was referring to the killing of an
Israeli soldier near the West Bank city of Hebron last month
during a clash with Hamas members.
</P>
<P>
"I want to tell you that to the best of my understanding these
attempts will continue," Mofaz said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "this war against terror and violence has a
price, and sometimes we pay for it."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli army has issued strict warnings to soldiers
that Hamas members are actively trying kidnap them.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers also have been told to abide strictly by regulations
on hitchhiking. Officers have been instructed to review the
regulations with their troops, and military policemen are out in
force to make sure soldiers are obeying them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
