<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major World News Summary at 0800 GMT, February 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA -- The World Bank announced Thursday that it would
provide Brazil in March with the first installment of one billion
U.S. dollar credit out of its total aid package of 4.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
World Bank representative in Brazil Gobind Nankne said that the
bank would discuss the releasing of the second 450-million-dollar
installment in April. Nankne said the bank would release three
billion dollars out of its total 4.5 billion package by December
1999. (Brazil-World Bank)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Some 250 families out of the 14,500 Cambodians at a
refugee camp in Thailand's Trat province have been sent home since
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, armed with food supplies, walked from Ban Khao
Phlu Camp to the Thai-Cambodian border to cross to their homeland,
the Bangkok Post reported Friday. The repatriation was financially
sponsored by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees,
which provided each refugee 250 baht (about seven U.S. dollars)
for transportation fees, agricultural foods and food supplies for
50-day consumption.(Thailand-Cambodia-Refugees)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUDAPEST -- Hungary will launch a sale of bonds abroad this
year in the amount of 500 million euros (about 590 million U.S.
dollars) to reduce the increasingly adverse balance of
international payments.
</P>
<P>
The issue, signed by the Ministry of finance and the relevant
banks Thursday, will have a maturity of ten years and will carry
an interest rate of 4.375 percent a year, said the Hungarian news
agency MTI. It will have been the first time for Hungary to issue
euro bonds. Hungarian Deputy Minister of Finance Thuma Jozhef did
not rule out the possibility that his country could issue more
bonds abroad in the years to come.(Hungary-Euro Bonds)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WARSAW -- Visiting Slovenian Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek said
Slovenia hoped to strengthen cooperation with Poland in the
economic area and ease integration with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
While meeting with his Polish counterpart Jerzy Buzek and
presidents of the parliament and the senate, Drnovsek expressed
his hope that Poland would support his country's efforts to join
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), the Polish news
agency reported. He said it was necessary for the two countries to
strengthen cooperation to ensure a speedy integration with the EU
since the two were among the first group of countries permitted to
enter. (Poland-Slovenia) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
