<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Urban Air Quality Remains Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The majority of China's cities
had stable air quality this week, according to the weekly air-
quality report released today by the China Environment Monitoring
Center.
</P>
<P>
From February 5 to 11, there were no cold fronts in the country'
s northern and eastern regions, and weather conditions were not
conducive to the elimination of pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The air-pollution index rose in some cities, while the
northwest city of Lanzhou suffered from serious air pollution last
week, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen and Haikou in the south enjoyed excellent air quality
during the period, while 16 other cities including Dalian, Zhuhai
and Shenzhen reported good air quality.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, Nanjing, Hangzhou in the east and nine other cities
reported slight air pollution and 13 cities including Beijing,
Guangzhou and Tianjin reported medium air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Along with Lanzhou, the northwestern cities of Urumqi and
Xining suffered from serious air pollution, all with an
overabundance of suspended particles in the air.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ivory Trade Helpful for Elephant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- British Environment Minister
Michael Meacher has said that the move to permit Zimbabwe and
Namibia to trade ivory with Japan on an experimental basis will
help the two countries generate revenue for elephant conservation.
</P>
<P>
"The funds raised from these ivory sales will be directed back
into elephant conservation where populations are flourishing, as
well as helping local communities living alongside the elephants,"
Meacher said in a statement released by the British High
Commission in Harare Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Elephant conservation and anti-poaching measures are expensive,
Meacher added.
</P>
<P>
The decision to allow the two African countries to engage in
experimental ivory trade was reached at a meeting of the Standing
Committee of the Convention on the International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) in Geneva Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A one-off experimental shipment of stock-piled ivory to Japan
from Namibia and Zimbabwe was permitted after United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP) identified that strict conservation
measures in both countries had been met.
</P>
<P>
The ivory contained in this shipment cannot be re-exported
outside Japan.
</P>
<P>
The standing committee also endorsed new measures which will
provide a comprehensive elephant monitoring system covering all of
Africa and southern Asia, Zimbabwe's Herald newspaper Friday
quoted Meacher as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The measures will include ETIS (Elephant Trade Information
System) to be funded by the United Kingdom for a year to monitor
both legal and illegal trading in ivory, and MIKE, a new elephant
population monitoring system which will involve the tracking of
elephant populations in range states across Africa and South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The European Union, United States and Japan pledged substantial
funding to get the system up and running. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Stamps Supremacy as He Reaches Quarterfinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Pete Sampras
proved to be an insurmountable mountain as he powered through a
two-set thriller to reach the quarter-finals of the Sybase Open at
California, United States.
</P>
<P>
He disposed of Argentine Martin Rodriguez 7-5, 6-3 with his
full arsenal of shots and all-court game, showing no sign of
rustiness even after ten-week absence from tennis.
</P>
<P>
The owner of 11 Grand Slam finals never face a break point,
slamming six aces, winning 94 percent of his first service points,
managing 36 of 45 net approaches.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the third-seeded Mark "Scud" Philippoussis of
Austrailia thrashed Dutchman John Van Lottum 6-2, 6-1, to set up a
quarter-finals match with American Justin Gimelstob, a 6-4, 7-6 (7-
3) winner over compatriot Chris Woodruff.
</P>
<P>
In a minor upset, Aussie veteran Mark Woodforde put out eighth
seed Ramon Delgado of Paraguay 6-2 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
