<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Trade Unions to Pressure Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) has resolved to put consumer boycotts on its agenda,
in attempts to resist relentless price increases, the Herald daily
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The boycotts are among the three resolutions adopted by the
national labor organization's general council at an extraordinary
meeting held here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the resolution by the organization's highest
decision-making body is part of its latest weapon to pressure the
government and industrialists into reversing the price increases,
following a ban on job mass stayaways by the government last year.
</P>
<P>
The stayaways were threatening to cripple the economy.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued at the end of the extraordinary meeting,
ZCTU Secretary-General Morgan Tsvangirai said the organization
will be going back to its structures to update workers on the
on-going tripartite meetings, and ponder the next move.
</P>
<P>
"The general council concluded that the government's sincerity
to take specific measures to arrest the current economic crisis is
questionable," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The government continues to dither on crucial matters to
address the escalating rate of inflation, the severe national
debt, the day-to-day increases in the prices of basic commodities,
devaluation of the local currency, etc., whereby the talks have
become inconclusive," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
