<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Declares 18-Month Ban on New Roads in Forests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. authorities on
Thursday declared an 18-month ban on building roads in national
forests, mainly in the west coast states.
</P>
<P>
"This interim policy will allow us to protect socially
important and ecologically valuable roadless areas while we
develop a protective and responsible long-term road policy," said
Mike Dombeck, chief of Forest Service at the U.S. Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
The new rule puts a temporary end to a year-long debate over
the forests. U.S. President Bill Clinton said in late 1997 that a
more environmentally-friendly approach would be taken toward road-
building in the 191 million-acre public forest system in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Environmental groups said the moratorium still left some 15
million acres of roadless national forest land unprotected from
building due to exemptions, including wholesale exclusions for
forests in Alaska, California and the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
"I assume he (Dombeck) knows we need to go farther than just a
new road policy to protect these last remaining roadless acres,"
said William Meadows, president of the Wilderness Society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Car Owners on Rise in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 45 percent of the motor
vehicles sold in 1998 in China went to private buyers and farmers
accounted for the largest proportion.
</P>
<P>
Last year, China turned out 1.62 million motor vehicles,
including over 500,000 cars, putting the number of private vehicle
owners at 12 million.
</P>
<P>
The private car market is demonstrating huge potential, as the
bank savings in the country hit 5.34 trillion yuan (643.37 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that 70 percent of the families in
Guangzhou, Beijing, and Shanghai intent to buy cars within the
next five to ten years. In 1998, individual buyers accounted for
89 percent of the cars sold by two major car dealers in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The rapid construction of expressways has also enlarged the
passenger transportation market, along with advances in vehicle-
production technology. At the same time, increasing rural demand
has promoted the upgrading of light-duty and mini vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The automobile industry as a whole is becoming stronger by
constantly expanding production scale. During the Ninth Five-Year-
Plan period (1996-2000), state investment in the country's large
auto-manufacturing groups is expected to reach as high as 91
percent of all investment in this sector.
</P>
<P>
At present, the nation's 13 leading car manufacturers account
for 92 percent of China's total motor-vehicle output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
