<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Committed to Skilled Migration Intake: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian federal
government Friday said it was committed to promoting the intake of
skilled migrants to Australia and boosting their English language
skills.
</P>
<P>
Australian Federal Immigration Minister Philip Ruddock said
Australia had a larger skilled migration program in a smaller
migration program overall last financial year than for the
previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
The total number of migrants entering Australia in the
financial year of 1997-1998, which ended on June 30, 1998, was
77,327, a fall of nearly 10 percent on the previous year,
according to Immigration and Multicultural Affairs Department
figures.
</P>
<P>
But the number of skilled migrants to Australia hit 25,985 in
1997-1998, an increase of just over 30 percent from 19,697 the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who was attending an Adult Migrant English
Program (AMEP) conference in Melbourne, said that since the launch
of AMEP in 1948, teaching English to migrants had become a
government priority to bind the nation together.
</P>
<P>
"In a country like Australia, which conducts an immigration
program which is so culturally diverse and people come from almost
170 different countries, if you didn't have English how would you
communicate?" he told the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
"If people are going to be able to have an opportunity to
participate fully, to use the skills that they've got, if they're
going to be able to use them beneficially, for themselves as well
as the nation, they need to be able to communicate effectively,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
