<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Professionals Benefit China's Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
And more than 300,000 Chinese people have traveled overseas for
further studies and work exchanges in the same period, 80,000 in
the last two years, according to the State Administration of
Foreign Experts Affairs (SAFEA).
</P>
<P>
Wan Xueyuan, director of SAFEA, revealed that increasing
numbers of foreign professionals are working in a wide range of
disciplines including, academia, science, construction, energy and
even in archeological fields.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese local governments at all levels have been benefited
from the introduction of overseas talent and they are getting more
enthusiastic about it," Wan said.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, there have been over 120 major
technical and industrial projects completed with the help of
foreign experts. Within the agricultural sector more than 270
breeding programs and seed planting projects have been realized
and foreign experts have been working in such diverse areas as
general agriculture, forestry, livestock breeding, fish farming
and on more than 30 advanced techniques for cultivation, soil
improvement and irrigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Professionals Benefit China's Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wan gave two examples of the successful importation of foreign
talent:
</P>
<P>
A nonferrous metal refinery plant in northwest China's Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region invited more than 30 relevant experts from
the United States, Russia, Japan and Germany to work alongside its
own professionals and as a result has completed 15 important
research projects. Now the plant's products have a ready market in
more than 10 countries and regions, making an annual profit of 28
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
 The SAFEA and the Chinese Ministry of Water Conservancy last
year invited six U.S. experts to investigate China's flood-hit
areas and later sent a 26-member delegation to the U.S. for a
month-long exchanges and training in flood control. The delegation
put forward "valuable suggestions" for China's future flood
control, which was appreciated by top Chinese leaders.
</P>
<P>
And a number of livestock breeds and seed plantings from Canada,
the U.S., Russia, Japan and other countries are becoming popular
in various areas of China, with noticeable results, Wan said.
</P>
<P>
Yet Wan is not satisfied with certain problems in the use of
foreign skills and techniques. He points out that there has been
slow progress in boosting and improving China's service and
information sectors and expressed concern about the repeated and
continual introduction in some areas of out-moded foreign
expertise and technical skills.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the SAFEA will focus its attentions on
planting, water conservancy and irrigation projects, the
restructuring and modern management of state-owned enterprises,
the building of new and hi-tech areas, and obviously the country's
key development and infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Wan said that he believes that there is much potential in the
use of overseas skills which can be tapped in the years to come.
</P>
</TEXT>
