<HEADLINE> 250 Cambodian Refugee Families in Thailand Sent Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Some 250 families out of the
14,500 Cambodians at a refugee camp in Thailand's Trat province
have been sent home since Monday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, armed with food supplies, walked from Ban Khao
Phlu Camp to the Thai-Cambodian border to cross to their homeland,
the Bangkok Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation was financially sponsored by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, which provided each
refugee 250 baht (about 7 U.S. dollars) for transportation fees,
agricultural foods and food supplies for 50-day consumption.
</P>
<P>
Cambodian authorities also agreed to provide six rai (0.96
hectares) of land in Battambang province for each refugee
families, Captain Nakhon Kosolsuraseenee, commander of Trat's
special navy task force, was quoted as saying. 
</P>
