<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists: Geothermal Effects May Result in Ozone Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists believed
that the destruction of ozone layers in the Antarctic and other
regions may have resulted partly from a geothermal effect produced
by large mountain ranges.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies indicated that the ozone-depletion phenomenon
has been detected over the 4,000-meter-high Qinghai-Tibet Plateau.
It has also been observed over the Rocky Mountain in South
American.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Daily reported that ozone depletion has aroused
public concern as the ozone layer is essential for protecting the
earth from solar ultra-violet radiation and because it is closely
related to climate and ecosystem changes.
</P>
<P>
Zou Han, a researcher from the Institute of Atmospheric Physics
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences said, studies showed that the
chemical pollution is a major factor causing the destruction of
ozone layers. However, those studies have not elaborated the
specific processes that causes destruction of ozone layers.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese scientists recently found that the global
distribution and zonal deviation of total ozone show apparent low
ozone distributions overt the three major mountainous regions with
the strongest one over Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Zou said, a seasonal variation in the regional distribution of
ozone layers indicates there is a spring maximum and autumn
minimum of ozone over the three regions.
</P>
<P>
The regionwide measurement of zonal distribution indicated that
maximum local ozone deficits occur during the spring and early
summer over the mountainous regions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ozone is regarded as one of the green houses that scientists
believe modifies the strength of ultraviolet radiation reaching
the earth.
</P>
<P>
Zou and his colleagues believed that there is a region of low
ozone distribution over the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau during the
summer.
</P>
<P>
The height of the plateau ranges from 3,000 to 5,000 meters
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
The relatively strong solar radiation and nature of the ground
surface makes the plateau a strong geothermal source for the
atmosphere.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary to Issue 500 Million Euros Worth of Bonds Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Hungary will launch a sale of
bonds abroad this year in the amount of 500 million euros (590
million U.S. dollars) to reduce the increasingly adverse balance
of international payments.
</P>
<P>
The issue, signed by the Ministry of finance and the relevant
banks Thursday, will have a maturity of ten years and will carry
an interest rate of 4.375 percent a year, said the Hungarian news
agency MTI.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Hungary's international payments rapidly worsened with
its unfavorable balance of nearly 2.264 billion dollars or 1.3
times more than in 1997, while foreign investments introduced into
the country in the year could only make up for two-thirds of the
unfavorable balance.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, the total amount of this imbalance will likely
continue to rise to 2.5-2.7 billion dollars, said the Hungarian
government, which has to repay a total of 1.9 billion dollars of
foreign debts within this year.
</P>
<P>
It will have been the first time for Hungary to issue euro
bonds. Hungarian Deputy Minister of Finance Thuma Jozhef did not
rule out the possibility that his country could issue more bonds
abroad in the years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
