<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Calls for National Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Senior General
Than Shwe Friday called for national unity to strive for
attainment of the union's goal for emergence of a peaceful, modern
and developed nation.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, chairman of the Myanmar State Peace and Development
Council, made the call in his message on the occasion of the
country's Union Day which falls on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Only when all the national people have firm national
convictions and concepts and practically implement them as
national policies, will all the nationals of the union smoothly
and straightly reach the aspired goal of the union," he said.
</P>
<P>
The national convictions and concepts are: non-disintegration
of the union, non-disintegration of national solidarity and
perpetuation of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
He called for safeguarding the national policies of these
convictions and concepts.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite its rich natural resources, Myanmar has
lagged behind in development in the absence of stability and peace
in the country due to the armed insurrections which had broken out
since the regaining of independence because of the machinations
by the colonialists.
</P>
<P>
He urged all the national people to strive in unison and
cooperation to firmly build the new peaceful, modern and developed
nation to be able to pay the historical debt of such lagging in
development.
</P>
<P>
He added that the strength of the union was great and solid and
its prestige was high in the times when national unity was
dynamic, and the nation's political, economic and social
conditions declined in the periods when national unity was weak.
</P>
<P>
He further called for combination of the three strengths of the
union -- the national people, the government and the Tatmadaw
(armed forces) -- as the consolidated force of the union.
</P>
<P>
On February 12, 1947, Myanmar ethnic leaders met at the Panlong
Conference in Shan state, sponsored under the leadership of the
late Myanmar independence hero General Aung San, and signed the
Panlong Agreement to strive in unity for the country's
independence from the British colonial rule. Myanmar won
independence on January 4, 1948. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
