<HEADLINE> Bank of Thailand Revises Export Growth target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central bank's Assistant Governor Kiettisak Meecharoen was
quoted Friday by The Nation as saying that the downward revision
of exports is due mainly to the slowdown in global economic
growth, primarily slower demand in the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Export prospects in the Asian markets have improved because
their economies have stabilized and shown signs of recovery. The
Chinese market, in particularly, remains strong and expanding at
an annual rate of 5 to 6 percent, Kiettisak said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Thai economy, Kiettisak said there are signs of
improvements in some key indicators. Sale of vehicles have climbed
since October last year while department stores and industrial
output also posted increases.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in the domestic economy should help offset a slowdown
in exports but the economy is still mired in uncertainty. The risk
factors are still out there. We believe that the economy should
expand after a contraction of 8.5 percent last year," Kiettisak
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
