<HEADLINE> 2 Senior Philippine Officials Probed on Bribery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Thursday that he will dismiss officials found to be
involved in a reported 75,000-U.S. dollar bribery attempt in
exchange for a deal with the government, the Journal newspaper
said.
</P>
<P>
Estrada was quoted as saying that he is still waiting for the
result of an inquiry by the National Bureau of Investigation (NBI)
into the supposed "misdelivery" of a package containing 3 million
pesos (75,000 U.S. dollars) to a senior government official.
</P>
<P>
In a preliminary report to Estrada, NBI Director Santiago
Toledo said that a businesswoman handed a package to an official
of the Department of Budget and Management.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the report as saying that the official was
asked to deliver the package to Budget and Management Secretary
Benjamin Diokno who found 3 million pesos inside the package.
</P>
<P>
The woman later returned to the office of the department and
demanded the return of the money which she said was "mistakenly
given," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to the NBI report, the woman claimed in her sworn
affidavit that the money was intended to the government's Deputy
Executive Secretary Vicente de la Serna and his executive
assistant Ricardo Fulgencio.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the woman, Mary Ann Maslog, and a publishing
firm have a deal of 200 million pesos (5 million U.S. dollars)
with the Department of Education, Culture and Sports.
</P>
<P>
The woman said in her affidavit that de la Serna and Fulgencio
"manifested their intention to participate in the deal but the
latter gave way in favor of Maslog in exchange for the 3 million
pesos," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In his Memorandum to Estrada, de la Serna denied the
accusation, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The NBI is digging deeper into the actual participation of the
two officials and the alleged 200-million-peso deal, the newspaper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
