<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relocation Well Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A massive relocation drive
involving more than 1 million residents at the Three Gorges
Reservoir Area is progressing smoothly, according to Guo Shuyan,
deputy director of the Three Gorges Project Construction
Commission under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, 160,000 locals, about 19 percent of the 840,
000 residents to be resettled, had been moved to new areas, Today'
s China Daily quoted a report from the Three Gorges commission's
Resettlement Bureau as saying.
</P>
<P>
Upon completion of the gigantic program in 2009, over 1.3
million residents are to have been resettled, including residents
from the lake area, Hubei Province and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
As part of the program, some 103,400 people were moved during
1993-97, at a cost of 8.575 billion yuan (1.04 billion U.S.
dollars), according to the resettlement bureau.
</P>
<P>
Houses and apartments, with a combined floor space of more than
4.14 million sq.m including urban and rural residents' workshops
have been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
Damming the main course of the Yangtze in 1997 symbolized the
end of the first-phase of the relocation, a bureau official said,
noting that the second phase (1998-2003) will be more difficult
than the project's first phase.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a critical period in the program as it will decide
whether the Three Gorges project can start storing water and begin
generating electricity as scheduled," the official said.
</P>
<P>
As many as 550,000 people are to be relocated during the second
phase, with 110,000 residents resettled annually.
</P>
<P>
To help ensure the relocated people's means of living and
production, more than 15 million sq.m of housing floor space is
planned, along with the construction of 684 km of roads, about 2,
260 km of power transmission lines and 3,312 km of
telecommunications lines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
