<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan Imposes Heavy Tariffs on Imports From Kirghizstan, Uzbekistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh Prime Minister Nurlan
Utebovich Balgimgaev announced Thursday that Kazakhstan will
impose heavy tariffs of up to 200 percent on some imports from
Kirghizstan and Uzbekistan in March in face of massive influx of
foreign goods into the country.
</P>
<P>
The currencies of Kirghizstan and Uzbekistan have greatly
depreciated due to the Russian financial turmoil, but the Kazakh
Tenge has remained steady. As a result, large quantities of
commodities from Kirghizstan and Uzbekistan, especially food and
tobaccos, have poured into Kazakhstan, setting Kazakh businesses
into a difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan had to raise its tariff rate on some Russian goods
in January.
</P>
<P>
A Kazakh official said the decision to increase the tax rate is
temporary and aims to protect Kazakhstan's economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The decision did not violate the taxation union of the
Commonwealth of Independent States and the free trade agreement
signed with Uzbekistan, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
