<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Pudong Seeking More Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Pudong New Area, a
rising financial and trade zone, has recently announced a series
of projects open to overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
They include a World Food City in the Lujiazui Financial and
Trade Zone and commercial facilities along Century Road, now under
construction.
</P>
<P>
The World Food City will consist of seven plazas featuring
cuisine of the world including Asian, European, and American
dishes, in a floor area of 60,000 square meters. The food plazas
will offer tastes from around the world and serve as a major
support facility to nearby office buildings.
</P>
<P>
Century Road, which runs for five kilometers across downtown
Pudong, is expected to become the busiest stretch of road in the
area.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funds are also welcome for the construction of
business buildings along the Century Road.
</P>
<P>
Pudong, which is separated from downtown Shanghai by the
Huangpu River, was officially opened to overseas investors in 1990.
Last year, it registered a gross domestic product of 71 billion
yuan, an increase of 16.8 percent over 1997, according to the
latest statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
