<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 Countries Sign Investments Protection Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries from
the Group of 15 (G-15) signed Thursday in the Jamaican city of
Montego Bay seven bilateral pacts on trade and private investments
protection.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Thursday from Montego Bay said that
Jamaica, which is hosting the group's ninth meeting, signed three
of the seven accords with three G-15 members.
</P>
<P>
The agreements signed between Jamaica and Indonesia, Egypt and
Zimbabwe, aim to attract private funds in bilateral investment
project and eliminate customs tariffs.
</P>
<P>
After the signing, Jamaican Premier Percival Patterson said
that the pacts will help the private sector's direct involvement
with the group's economic policy.
</P>
<P>
The four other agreements were signed between India and
Indonesia; Indonesia and Zimbabwe; India and Zimbabwe; and
Malaysia and Senegal.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 15 has grown to 17 member states and includes
Algeria, Argentina, Chile, India, Kenya, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
G-15 states account for 30 percent of the world's population
and produce 2 trillion dollars in goods, or nearly 40 percent of
the gross domestic product of all developing nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
