<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Household Spending Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada's average household
spent 49,950 Canadian dollars (32,967 U.S. dollars) on everything
in 1997, virtually unchanged from 1996, Statistics Canada reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Personal income taxes contnue to make up the largest share of
household spending. In 1997, an average of 21 cents of every
dollar went towards personal income taxes, followed by 20 cents
for shelter,12 cents for transportation and 11 cents for food.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 36 cents were spent on a variety of items such as
recreation, personal insurance and pension contributions, clothig,
household operations, the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
The average amount paid on personal income taxes in 1997 was
estimated at 10,630 Canadian dollars, essentially unchanged from
1996 (10,750 Canadian dollars), households spent an average of 9,
870 Canadian dollars on shelter costs, 5,700 Canadian dollars on
food and 6,200 on transportation, also virtually unchanged from
the previous year, said the agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
