<HEADLINE> Colombian Bankers Investigated For Taking Drug Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- At least 17 top-ranking bank
executives are being investigated by Colombian police on charges
of accepting money from members of the Cali drug cartel,
newspapers here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The press published a list of bank vice-presidents and managers
charged with illicit enrichment, accepting drug money, complicity,
and prevarication through omission.
</P>
<P>
Most of the bank executives head branch offices in the city of
Cali, where drug lords Miguel and Gilberto Orejuela and other
traffickers, most of whom have been jailed, had opened accounts.
</P>
<P>
Over 20 legislators have been sentenced to prison for taking
bribes from drug traffickers in recent years, following a scandal
prompted by accusations that former president Ernesto Samper --
now living in Spain -- had funded his political campaign with drug
money given by the Cali cartel. 
