<HEADLINE> Brazilian, Paraguayan Presidents Meet on Currency Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso and his Paraguayan counterpart Raul Cubas
Thursday discussed the effects of the devaluation on Brazil's
currency, the real, and the strengthening of the South American
Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
The two also confirmed that Mercosur's next summit would be
held on February 21 in the Brazilian city of Rio de Janeiro.
Participants in the Rio summit will study measures to counter the
adverse effects of the real's depreciation on trade within the
bloc.
</P>
<P>
Cubas, who arrived here Thursday morning for a one-day visit,
said the four presidents of Mercosur -- made up of Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay -- would also discuss the same issues
during a European Union-Mercosur forum in Rio on the same day.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinetti met with Cardoso on
February 3 to prepare the summit. Argentinian President Carlos
Menem will also meet with Cardoso on Friday in the Brazilian city
of Campos do Jordao.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian business representatives said the real's devaluation
could boost Brazilian exports to other Mercosur countries by 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
They said that due to the weak real, Brazil's 1998 trade
deficit of 410 million U.S. dollars with its Mercosur partners
could turn into a 710-million-dollar surplus.
</P>
<P>
They said Brazil's total trade surplus could soar to 1.1
billion dollars this year compared to one billion in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
