<HEADLINE> Indiana Judge Not to Make Decision Until Tyson Appeals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Indiana judge who sent
Mike Tyson to prison in 1992 will make decision only after the
boxer decides to appeal his sentence in Maryland, Tyson's
probation officer said today.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's lawyers have 30 days to decide whether to appeal the
one-year sentence made by a Maryland's judge Friday for assaulting
two motorists in a minor accident in August.
</P>
<P>
Tyson pleaded no contest to the charges. "We have not received
any paperwork (from Maryland)," said George Walker, Tyson's
probation officer in Indiana, where he was convicted of rape in
1992. "We had a case conference a couple days ago where we took
into consideration the fact Tyson could appeal the sentencing in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
"So given that situation, we once again have taken a wait-and-
see posture for the next couple weeks to see if in fact he does
appeal."
</P>
<P>
An appeal could lead to jury trial and an even longer jail term
in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
"If he does not appeal, then we'll set a hearing locally and
move forward on that," Walker said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maryland sentence, Tyson would be eligible in 60 days
to be moved to a pre-release center, which he could leave during
the day in order to train and return at night.
</P>
<P>
With Johnson's permission, Tyson could travel out of state to
fight, and with good behavior, he could be released from custody
in seven months.
</P>
<P>
Walker said he has not indicated to judge Patricia Gifford in
Indiana whether he thinks Tyson should serve more time.
</P>
<P>
"That's not my decision. I wouldn't even say it's my
recommendation. In fact, I don't know particularly right now what
my recommendation would be. It would be unfair to say that,"
Walker said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
