<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Can New Zealand Government Survive Confidence Vote? (1)  By Zhou Cipu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Members of the New Zealand
Parliament are coming to Wellington these days to resume the
session on February 16 after a two-month adjournment.
</P>
<P>
When the new round of session starts, the first and immediate
challenge Prime Minister Jenny Shipley and her National-led
minority government will face is whether they can survive a
confidence vote and prevent an early election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling National Party only has 44 seats in the 120-strong
Parliament. The National Party and the NZ First formed a coalition
government after the previous general election in 1996. The
coalition fell apart last August because of severe differences
between the two parties on a number of issues, especially on the
sales of the government-owned shares in the Wellington
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The collapse of the coalition government reduced the votes the
National Party could count on in the Parliament to 62 from the
previous 70. Although the foundation of the National-led minority
government, which Prime Minister Shipley set up after the
coalition government, was unstable, it eventually weathered the
test of a confidence vote last September.
</P>
<P>
Before the recess of the Parliament last year, independent MP
Deborah Morris quit the Parliament, cutting the National-led
minority government's support on confidence issues to just 61
votes in the 120-seat Parliament. The 61 votes come from
National-own 44, ACT's eight, Mauri Pacific's five, United MP
Peter Dunne and three independent MPs.
</P>
<P>
It seems the current government is hanging on by a thin thread,
and can be deprived of its majority support status in the
Parliament and brought down with just one MP switching sides.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of last year, especially around the breakup
of the coalition government, the Labor Party and other opposition
parties cried out for an early election. Although the National-led
minority government tided over the confidence-vote crisis last
September, their demand for an early election was not weakened. In
view of the poor performance of the New Zealand economy and low
support rate for the National Party in polls at that time, they
pinned their hopes for bringing down the government on the
February round of the Parliament's session. The Labor Party, which
enjoyed around 48 support rate in polls at that time, was poised
to lead the government after the next election.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that even the government organs responsible for
election affairs had doubts at that time about Shipley's ability
to keep her government in power until the end of its full term in
November, and they began preparations for election in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Can New Zealand Government Survive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The dissolution of the coalition government might be a good
tiding for the National Party. It has enabled Shipley to hold a
stable government and implement the National's economic policies,
such as privatization of state-owned companies, encouragement of
business competition, and advocation of free trade.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand is a trading country. Of every 10 dollars of New
Zealand's national income or GDP, around three dollars comes from
exports.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce the losses caused by the Asian financial
crisis, the government has been active in expanding New Zealand's
traditional markets in West Europe, the United States and
Australia and opening up new ones in South Asia and Latin
America, while maintaining its close economic links with East
Asia. It also announced a series of "Policies for Progress" to
stimulate the economic activity, expand exports, promote tourism
industry and increase migrants.
</P>
<P>
Through the adjustment in the value of the New Zealand dollar,
a flexible labor market and reduction of input prices such as
electricity, motor vehicles, petrol and diesel and personal
income tax, the government provided an economic environment that
allowed New Zealand exporters to move quickly in response to
global challenges.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of 1998, New Zealand's economic situation
took a favorable turn, thanks to the government efforts. The
country has also benefited from the steady economic growth in
West Europe and the United States and from improved economic
situations in Asian countries. It is fortunate that the recent
financial turmoil in Brazil has had little effects on the New
Zealand economy.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released by Statistics New Zealand showed
that expanded New Zealand exports in the second half of 1998
enabled the country to increase the value of its exports by five
percent to 12.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 compared with the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
while New Zealand shares rising by an average 30 percent in
less than five months, business confidence in the country has
returned to pre-1998 levels. Its GDP ended six-month shrink and
registered a 0.7 percent increase in the third quarter of 1998 and
is expected to keep growing in the fourth quarter. The New
Zealand dollar has regained some of its shine, interest rates
remain at 30-year lows, and prices grew only by 0.4 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
According to New Zealand Treasurer Bill Birch, the country's
economic growth would reach three percent in the year to March
next year, nearly double the 1.6 percent rise in GDP forecast by
the Treasury last December and the New Zealand government would
run a budget surplus again this year, rather than dipping 52
million NZ dollars (28 million U.S. dollars) into the red as
predicted in December.
</P>
<P>
The country is really emerging from economic recession or even
has shrugged off the recessionary blues. Its economy is now on
the track of growth.
</P>
<P>
In such an economic situation, a growing number of New Zealand
people favor political stability in the country. The latest poll
showed that the support rate for the National Party improved and
the support rate for the Labor Party dropped.
</P>
<P>
Lately, the Labor Party and other opposition parties have all
kept silent on the issue of an early election. Up to now, no one
among the 17 non-National MPs has come out, willing to bring a
pre-mature end to the government. It is almost certain that Prime
Minister Shipley and her government will serve their full term to
November unless some unexpected things arise all of a sudden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
