<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Arrested in Charlton FC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Four men have been arrested as
part of an investigation into a possible betting scam at top
football grounds.
</P>
<P>
The men, only one of whom is a Briton, were arrested on
suspicion of burglary at Charlton Athletic's ground, The Valley,
in south-east London.
</P>
<P>
Their arrest followed alleged damage to electrical equipment
connected to the ground's floodlights.
</P>
<P>
The British man arrested was employed by a security firm at The
Valley.
</P>
<P>
English Football Association (FA) acting chief executive David
Davies said: "Football may have been the intended victim of an
outside attack. That attack has been thwarted for which we are all
grateful."
</P>
<P>
The FA will be contacting all Premier League and Football
League clubs.
</P>
<P>
"The integrity of the game is crucial to us all," he said.
</P>
<P>
The men are in custody where they are being interviewed by the
Metropolitan Police Organised Crime Group.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman said the force was liaising closely with the
Football Association, Premier League and Football League.
</P>
<P>
"We have been given by the FA a list of previous games where
the power supply has failed," she added.
</P>
<P>
There has been conjecture since late 1997 linking floodlight
failures to a Far East betting ring.
</P>
<P>
A single Premiership match is worth millions of pounds to a
betting syndicate.
</P>
<P>
So far as some bets are concerned in parts of Asia, as soon as
the game has passed the halfway mark the result stands even if it
then ends prematurely.
</P>
<P>
Asian syndicates could cash in if a game were to end when the
result was favourable.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Graham Sharpe, of bookmaker William Hill, said the
same rules do not apply in Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Domestically, all bets are void if a match is abandoned, you
keep your stake money but it's impossible to make any money," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the rules were designed to guard against any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
A little over a year ago, Asian gambling syndicates were
accused of arranging a floodlight failure at a Premier League
match.
</P>
<P>
And in the same season, Scotland Yard were investigating a
power failure at the Wimbledon-Arsenal game at Selhurst Park in
south London. There were problems also at Derby and West Ham.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
