<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Consumers to Benefit Market Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
consumers will benefit liberalization of markets such as
telecommunications, a European commissioner told a new local
magazine in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Karel Van Miert, EU commissioner for competition, said in the
first issue of Trends International published here Thursday that
the consumers have already started to see the benefits. "They will
be seeing more in the near future, no doubt," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 10 out of 15 EU member states, full liberalization of all
telecommunications markets was achieved as of January 1, 1998, the
commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
"That is a pretty record given the complexity of the problem.
Even in the first year of liberalization, there were numerous new
operators. They entered the market and are now challenging the
former monopoly operators," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Take a look at the price cuts. International calls, for
example, have gone down by 3 to 27 percent in the different member
states," Van Miert said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
