<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Competition Policy Getting Tougher: Van Miert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European single currency,
the euro, is expected to lead to tougher competition with a wave
of new mergers on the horizon and the European Union (EU) is
facing trial of its competition policy, European Commissioner
Karel Van Miert has said.
</P>
<P>
But the EU's executive branch said it is ready for the new
trend, Van Miert told the first issue of a local business magazine
that was published here Thursday
</P>
<P>
The European Commission is planning a series of reforms
measures, both as regards anti-trust legislation and state aid,
in a bid to ensure that the EU policy framework can continue to
face the challenges of future enlargement, newly liberalized
markets, increased globalization and the changed situation with
the euro, Van Miert said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the February 11 issue of Trends
International, Van Miert said that adapting the policy framework
effectively means building on past experience as well, and this is
why control of mergers will continue to be a major priority.
</P>
<P>
"The last few years have seen a new wave, mainly due to
globalization and technological change. Now the euro is here we
have to be even more vigilance," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said the euro will clearly lead to national
markets opening up and becoming more European and will push many
firms towards joint ventures and mergers. There has already been a
significant increase in the number of complaints submitted to the
commission, the EU's executive branch mainly responsible for
proposing and enforcing legislation.
</P>
<P>
Another priority for the commission is reducing state aid in
the 15-country EU, Van Miert said. This is all the more necessary
given Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) and the commitment to
enlargement. As far as classic anti-trust action is concerned, the
top priority will be identifying, prohibiting and, where
appropriate, fining cartels, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We will also continue to pursue cases where the free market is
being hindered by restrictions on parallel trade between member
states. Sectors currently being liberalized will also come in for
close scrutiny. Fair competition has to be enforced in those
sectors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Finally, my staff and I will continue with the push for
liberalization in the field of air transport by insisting on the
application of competition directives," the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
Observers here in the Trends International magazine predict
that tougher competition such as new merger wave and an
ever-growing awareness of unfair trade practices in Europe are
putting great pressure on the European Commission. Therefore 1999
will also be a tougher year for the EU executive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Launches Attacks in Both No-Fly Zones in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- In addition to attacks
Thursday in the northern no-fly zone, U.S. warplanes launched new
attacks against Iraqi air defense targets in the southern no-fly
zone in Iraq, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Capt. Mike Doubleday said the attacks in the
southern no-fly zone occurred at about 10:45 a.m. EST (1545 GMT).
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. Air Force and Navy fighter jets struck two
anti-aircraft missile sites and associated facilities like radar
and equipment after a pair of Iraqi MiG-23s flew into the no-fly
zone.
</P>
<P>
The incidents took place near Al Habbriyah, about 135 miles
(217 km) southwest of Baghdad, and near Al Amarah, about 170 miles
(273 km) southeast of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"All aircraft have returned to their bases safely and battle
damage assessment is ongoing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, U.S. fighter jets launched attacks against at
least five Iraqi targets in the northern no-fly zone with no
damage to U.S. aircraft and no injuries to U.S. pilots, another
Pentagon spokesman, Lt. Col. Steve Campbell, said.
</P>
<P>
In the first incident, between about 12:15 p.m. and 12:30 p.m.
local time (0915 and 0930 GMT), a U.S. Air force F-15E strike
Eagle observed Iraqi anti-aircraft artillery fire and was
"illuminated" by an Iraqi radar system near the northern city of
Mosul.
</P>
<P>
"Acting in self-defense, one F-15E dropped four GBU12
precision-guided bombs on a surface-to-air missile communications
site," a Defense Department statement said. Two other F-15Es
launched a missile and dropped four bombs on an Iraqi
surface-to-air missile system.
</P>
<P>
An hour later, U.S. pilots retaliated in three separate
incidents, with F-15Es bombing a SAM site and a communications
site, and an Air Force F-16CJ launching a high-speed
anti-radiation missile at an Iraqi radar site.
</P>
<P>
Doubleday said that in total, U.S. warplanes operating from
land and sea bases attacked at least seven targets in both the
northern and southern no-fly zones Thursday, targets ranging from
Iraqi missile communication sites to radar sites.
</P>
<P>
The latest attacks are in line with the Pentagon's more
aggressive policy in retaliation against Iraq's defiance in the
no-fly zones, which Baghdad declared violation by U.S. and British
aircraft of its sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Doubleday said U.S. and British attacks since December had had
a "grave impact" on Iraq's air defense system and weakened them
considerably.
</P>
<P>
"We believe we have been effective in hitting the targets
threatening coalition forces and our intention is that as long as
they continue these provocative actions we will continue to
respond," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
