WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton and
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder Thursday renewed threats of
NATO air strikes should Kosovo peace talks at Rambouillet, near
Paris, fail.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder told reporters after his meeting with Clinton at the
White House they agreed that "the international community cannot
and will not accept either delay or failure and thus made clear a
willingness, as before and without hesitation, to undertake a NATO
strike."
</P>
<P>
He said he and Clinton also agreed that the talks, which began
last Saturday, must produce a result "in the time that has been
set aside." He stressed that time limits imposed on the Serbian
and Kosovo Albanian sides would not be extended.
</P>
<P>
The six-nation Contact Group has given the warring sides two
weeks to reach a deal to end the 11-month Kosovo conflict, but
diplomatic sources say the talks have not moved much beyond
opening draft proposals on political aspects of an accord.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder was in Washington for a one-day visit for what was
described as an informal meeting with Clinton, at which they
discussed Kosovo, the April NATO summit in Washington, the world
economic situation and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
