<HEADLINE> NOAA Sets Up Web Site on Global Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration announced here recently that it has
set up a global warming web site named "A Paleo Perspective On
Global Warming," to help general public and journalists understand
global warming.
</P>
<P>
The web site, also called "handbook" on global warming,
explains global warming and the greenhouse effect, and describes
how they relate to the issues of atmospheric ozone change. Out
from other global warming web sites, it places current warming in
the context of past temperature variations through the use of
paleoclimatic data.
</P>
<P>
It tells how scientists study global warming, including how
they study variations in the Earth's temperature using satellite,
instrumental and paleoclimatic data extending as far back as
millions of years. It also provides scientists with records of
past climatic change extending back centuries and millennia.
</P>
<P>
The web site is:
http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/paleo/perspectives.html. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
