<DOCNO> XIE19990212.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Troops Preparing for Possible Kosovo Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain said Thursday that its
troops will support any peacekeeping operations if a deal is
reached between the warring factions in the Serbian province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary George Robertson told parliament that his
ministry is preparing forces which could make up part of a NATO
presence in Kosovo if a peace deal between Yugoslav Serb
authorities and separatist ethnic Albanians is struck.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the troops could move at a moment's notice, an
advance force of tanks, armored vehicles, artillery and some 200
key logistics personnel is being sent to the region Monday, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The United Kingdom is determined to play its part in
supporting a negotiated settlement to Kosovo. But we will only
deploy our forces in support of an operation with a clear mission
and clear objectives and alongside our allies," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
But he added that no decision had yet been taken to send troops
or equipment into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group on former Yugoslavia, comprising Britain,
Germany, France, Italy, Russia and the United States, has given
Serbian and Kosovo Albanian leaders, who are currently conducting
peace talks in France, two weeks to reach a deal to end their
almost year-long conflict.
</P>
<P>
Reports say the talks at the French town of Rambouillet near
Paris have not made much progress beyond opening draft proposals
on political aspects of an accord.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said it was unclear whether a NATO force would be
needed to support a peace agreement although he said the talks
were making some progress.
</P>
<P>
"A military force which is to be effective must be assembled
well in advance and this means we and our allies must have forces
in the region ready to go into action at short notice," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is for this reason that the government has decided today to
send to the region at the beginning of next week the vehicles and
other heavy equipment of the units which would form the leading
elements of any deployment."
</P>
<P>
About 200 logistics personnel would be sent to Greece and
Macedonia, which borders on Kosovo, to prepare for the arrival of
this equipment but most troops from the units involved would
remain at their bases on standby to move.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary also insisted that the troops would only
be sent in if a deal was reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
