<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Worry About Fiscal Incentives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Council of the Foreign
Investors in Romania expressed their worries on the cancellation
of the fiscal incentives for the investors, said a Thursday report
of the Rompres news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian parliament Monday passed a proposition of the
government to suspend preferential policy for foreign investments,
according to which the custom tariffs and value-added taxes are
exempted for any foreign investment. The policy, approved last
year, was guaranteed then by the government to be in place for at
least five years.
</P>
<P>
The foreign investors believed that the Romanian government has
other solutions likely to increase the budget revenues, one of
these being a better Finance Ministry tax collection.
</P>
<P>
The Council of the Foreign Investors in Romania is made up of
60 foreign companies that have made investments worth about 2.5
billion U.S. dollars, with ABN AMRO Bank, McDonald's, Citibank,
Chase Manhattan, Coca Cola Services, Mobifon, Mobilrom, Daewoo
Corporation, Societe Generale, British American Tobacco, Nestle,
Shell, Tuborg, Kraft Jacobs Suchard, and BERD being just some of
them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
